{"title_page": "Al-Hasan ibn 'Ali al-Barbahari", "text_new": "{{short description|10th-century Islamic theologian}}\n{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Islam]]\n|  region          = Iraq scholar\n|  era             = Medieval era\n|  image      =\n|  caption   =\n|  name             = '''al-\u1e24asan ibn \u02bbAl\u012b al-Barbah\u0101r\u012b'''|\n|  birth_place      =  [[Baghdad]], Iraq\n|  death_date       =  941 CE\n| denomination = [[Sunni]]\n|  jurisprudence = [[Hanbali]]\n|  creed = [[Athari]]\n|  main_interests   = [[Aqidah]]<br /> [[Fiqh]]\n|  influences       = [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal]]\n|  influenced       = [[Ibn Battah]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gibb |first1=H.A.R. |last2=Kramers |first2=J.H. |last3=Levi-Provencal |first3=E. |last4=Schacht |first4=J. |title=Encyclopaedia of Islam (New Edition) |volume=Volume I (A\u2013B) |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden, Netherlands |date=1986 |origyear=1st. pub. 1960 |isbn=9004081143 |page=1040}}\n</ref>\n|  notable_ideas    = \n}}\n'''Al-\u1e24asan ibn \u02bbAl\u012b al-Barbah\u0101r\u012b''' was a [[Muslim]] theologian from [[Iraq]]. He was a scholar and [[fiqh|jurist]] who played an important role in the [[Sunni]] struggle against the [[Shia|S\u0332h\u0332\u012b\u02bfa]] missionaries and successfully opposed the progress of [[Mu'tazilism]] in the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] during the 10th\u201311th (4th\u20135th [[Anno Hegirae|AH]]) centuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-2/al-barbahari-SIM_1224?s.num=0&s.f.s2_parent=s.f.book.encyclopaedia-of-islam-2&s.q=barbahari|title=al-Barbah\u0101r\u012b |publisher= Brill Reference|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> His books include creedal and methodological refutations against  the Shias, [[Qadariyah|Qadaris]], Mu'tazilis and [[Ash'ari]]s.\n\n==Biography==\nAl-Barbahari was born in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]], and learned from the students of [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal]]. In addition, al-Barbahari took Ibn Hanbal's views and championed them.\n\nAl-Barbahari had several widely known students, including the famed scholar [[Ibn Battah]]. His status as an authority within the Hanbali school was not universal, however, and al-Barbahari and his students were often in conflict with [[Abu Bakr al-Khallal]], generally considered to be the sole preserver and codifier of the school.<ref name=chris>[[Christopher Melchert]], ''The Formation of the Sunni Schools of Law: 9th\u201310th Centuries C.E.'', p. 150. Issue 4 of Studies in Islamic Law and Society, V. 4. Leiden: Brill Publishers, 1997. {{ISBN|9789004109520}}</ref> While al-Barbahari contributed little to jurisprudence, he was well known as a polemicist. His book ''Sharh as-Sunnah'' was written to educate the Hanbalites in methods to identify heretics.<ref>Joseph Norment Bell, ''Love Theory in Later \u1e24anbalite Islam'', p. 49. Albany, NY: SUNY Press, 1979. {{ISBN|9780791496237}}</ref> <ref>Richard M. Frank, Early Islamic Theology: The Mu'tazilites and al-Ash'ari, Texts and studies on the development and history of kal\u0101m, vol. 2, p. 172. Farnham: Ashgate Publishing, 2007. {{ISBN|9780860789789}}</ref><ref>''A Medieval Critique of Anthropomorphism: Ibn Al-Jawz\u012b's Kit\u0101b Akhb\u0101r A\u1e63-\u1e62if\u0101t'', p. 98. Ed. Merlin L. Swartz. Volume 46 of Islamic philosophy and theology: Texts and studies. Leiden: Brill Publishers, 2002. {{ISBN|9789004123762}}</ref>\n\n===Defender Of The Sunnah===\nAl-Barbahari was the leader of a number of protests against other sects during the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] in Baghdad. His audience was strong in the Hanbalite quarter of the city.<ref>Gerhard B\u00f6wering, ''The Mystical Vision of Existence in Classical Islam: The Qur'anic Hermeneutics of the Sufi Sahl At-Tustari, Parts 283\u2013896'', p. 89. Berlin: [[Walter de Gruyter]], 1979. {{ISBN|9783110837056}}</ref> He was very influential among the urban lower classes, and exploited popular grievances to foment what often turned into mob violence against religious minorities and supposed sinners.<ref name=ira>Ira M. Lapidus, ''Islamic Societies to the Nineteenth Century: A Global History'', p. 192. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2012. {{ISBN|9780521514415}}</ref><ref name=joel61>Joel L. Kraemer, ''Humanism in the Renaissance of Islam: The Cultural Revival During the Buyid Age'', p. 61. Volume 7 of Studies in Islamic culture and history. Leiden: Brill Publishers, 1992. {{ISBN|9789004097360}}</ref> \n\nFrom 921 until his death in 941 CE, al-Barbahari fought for orthodox Sunni thought and practice, leading masses of Sunnis in actions to stop the sale of wine and visits to the \"tombs of certain religious figures\", destroy musical instruments, combat Shiism and [[Mu'tazilism]].<ref name=\"Mouline-2014-29\">{{cite book |last1=Mouline |first1=Nabil |title=The Clerics of Islam: Religious Authority and Political Power in Saudi Arabia |date=2014 |publisher=Yale University Press |page=29 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tOEdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=al-Barbahari+d.941&source=bl&ots=w5XJ37Ctvp&sig=ACfU3U2Sc4h363_31OT3KOeevWq7ETcD-A&hl=en&ppis=_c&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjygP-6g-PoAhXTX80KHYGLCtIQ6AEwAHoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=al-Barbahari%20d.941&f=false |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Under the influence of al-Barbahari and popular pressure of his followers, the [[Caliph]]s [[Al-Muqtadir]] and [[Al-Qahir]] enforced Hanbalism as the state creed, exiling and imprisoning al-Barbahari's enemies and even burying renowned Muslim historian [[Muhammad ibn Jarir al-Tabari]] -- considered a heretic by most Hanbalites at the time -- in secret due to fears of mob violence were a funeral to be held at the public graveyard.<ref name=joel61/>\n\nThe efforts of al-Barbahari and the Baghdad Hanbalites were put to an end in 935 by the new Caliph [[Ar-Radi]]. Al-Barbahari had ordered groups to check any homes suspected of containing wine or musical instruments. The crowds confiscated from shops and physically enforced female entertainers to leave their practices.<ref>Christopher Melchert, ''Studies in Islamic Law and Society'', vol. 4, p. 151. Leiden: Brill Publishers, 1997.</ref> Ar-Radi ended the favored status of the Hanbalites. \n\n==Thought==\nLike other Hanbali, Barbahari strongly opposed ''[[Bid\u02bbah]]'' (religious innovation), defined as anything that the first generation of Muslims, (known as the [[Companions of the Prophet]] or ''Sahabah''), \"did not do\".<ref name=cook-2000-109/> Thus he taught that \"whoever asserts that there is any part of Islam with which the Companions of the Prophet did not provide us has called them [the Companions of the Prophet] liars\".<ref name=cook-2000-109/> While opposed to the [[reason]] provided it was put to good use and did not contradict doctrine such as [[God_in_Islam#Attributes|divine attributes]].<ref name=\"Mouline-2014-29\"/> Nonetheless, he wrote,  \"You don't ask 'Why?' and 'How?' Theology, polemic, disputation, and argument are and innovation which casts doubt into the heart\".<ref name=cook-2000-109>Cook, Michael, ''The Koran, a very short introduction, Oxford University Press, 2000, p.109</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Islamic scholars]]\n* [[Notable Hanbali Scholars]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Hanbali scholars}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Al-Barbahaaree}}\n[[Category:940 deaths]]\n[[Category:Hanbalis]]\n[[Category:Sunni Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:People from Baghdad]]\n[[Category:Hadith scholars]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Sunni Muslims]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:10th-century people of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:10th-century Arabs]]\n[[Category:10th-century jurists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|10th-century Islamic theologian}}\n{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Islam]]\n|  region          = Iraq scholar\n|  era             = Medieval era\n|  image      =\n|  caption   =\n|  name             = '''al-\u1e24asan ibn \u02bbAl\u012b al-Barbah\u0101r\u012b'''|\n|  birth_place      =  [[Baghdad]], Iraq\n|  death_date       =  941 CE\n| denomination = [[Sunni]]\n|  jurisprudence = [[Hanbali]]\n|  creed = [[Athari]]\n|  main_interests   = [[Aqidah]]<br /> [[Fiqh]]\n|  influences       = [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal]]\n|  influenced       = [[Ibn Battah]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gibb |first1=H.A.R. |last2=Kramers |first2=J.H. |last3=Levi-Provencal |first3=E. |last4=Schacht |first4=J. |title=Encyclopaedia of Islam (New Edition) |volume=Volume I (A\u2013B) |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden, Netherlands |date=1986 |origyear=1st. pub. 1960 |isbn=9004081143 |page=1040}}\n</ref>\n|  notable_ideas    = \n}}\n'''Al-\u1e24asan ibn \u02bbAl\u012b al-Barbah\u0101r\u012b''' was a [[Muslim]] theologian from [[Iraq]]. He was a scholar and [[fiqh|jurist]] who played an important role in the [[Sunni]] struggle against the [[Shia|S\u0332h\u0332\u012b\u02bfa]] missionaries and successfully opposed the progress of [[Mu'tazilism]] in the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] during the 10th\u201311th (4th\u20135th [[Anno Hegirae|AH]]) centuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-2/al-barbahari-SIM_1224?s.num=0&s.f.s2_parent=s.f.book.encyclopaedia-of-islam-2&s.q=barbahari|title=al-Barbah\u0101r\u012b |publisher= Brill Reference|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> His books include creedal and methodological refutations against  the Shias, [[Qadariyah|Qadaris]], Mu'tazilis and [[Ash'ari]]s.\n\n==Biography==\nAl-Barbahari was born in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]], and learned from the students of [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal]]. In addition, al-Barbahari took Ibn Hanbal's views and championed them.\n\nAl-Barbahari had several widely known students, including the famed scholar [[Ibn Battah]]. His status as an authority within the Hanbali school was not universal, however, and al-Barbahari and his students were often in conflict with [[Abu Bakr al-Khallal]], generally considered to be the sole preserver and codifier of the school.<ref name=chris>[[Christopher Melchert]], ''The Formation of the Sunni Schools of Law: 9th\u201310th Centuries C.E.'', p. 150. Issue 4 of Studies in Islamic Law and Society, V. 4. Leiden: Brill Publishers, 1997. {{ISBN|9789004109520}}</ref> While al-Barbahari contributed little to jurisprudence, he was well known as a polemicist. His book ''Sharh as-Sunnah'' was written to educate the Hanbalites in methods to identify heretics.<ref>Joseph Norment Bell, ''Love Theory in Later \u1e24anbalite Islam'', p. 49. Albany, NY: SUNY Press, 1979. {{ISBN|9780791496237}}</ref> <ref>Richard M. Frank, Early Islamic Theology: The Mu'tazilites and al-Ash'ari, Texts and studies on the development and history of kal\u0101m, vol. 2, p. 172. Farnham: Ashgate Publishing, 2007. {{ISBN|9780860789789}}</ref><ref>''A Medieval Critique of Anthropomorphism: Ibn Al-Jawz\u012b's Kit\u0101b Akhb\u0101r A\u1e63-\u1e62if\u0101t'', p. 98. Ed. Merlin L. Swartz. Volume 46 of Islamic philosophy and theology: Texts and studies. Leiden: Brill Publishers, 2002. {{ISBN|9789004123762}}</ref>\n\n===Defender Of The Sunnah===\nAl-Barbahari was the leader of a number of protests against other sects during the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] in Baghdad. His audience was strong in the Hanbalite quarter of the city.<ref>Gerhard B\u00f6wering, ''The Mystical Vision of Existence in Classical Islam: The Qur'anic Hermeneutics of the Sufi Sahl At-Tustari, Parts 283\u2013896'', p. 89. Berlin: [[Walter de Gruyter]], 1979. {{ISBN|9783110837056}}</ref> He was very influential among the urban lower classes, and exploited popular grievances to foment what often turned into mob violence against religious minorities and supposed sinners.<ref name=ira>Ira M. Lapidus, ''Islamic Societies to the Nineteenth Century: A Global History'', p. 192. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2012. {{ISBN|9780521514415}}</ref><ref name=joel61>Joel L. Kraemer, ''Humanism in the Renaissance of Islam: The Cultural Revival During the Buyid Age'', p. 61. Volume 7 of Studies in Islamic culture and history. Leiden: Brill Publishers, 1992. {{ISBN|9789004097360}}</ref> \n\nFrom 921 until his death in 941 CE, al-Barbahari fought for orthodox Sunni thought and practice, leading masses of Sunnis in actions to stop the sale of wine and visits to the \"tombs of certain religious figures\", destroy musical instruments, combat Shiism and [[Mu'tazilism]].<ref name=\"Mouline-2014-29\">{{cite book |last1=Mouline |first1=Nabil |title=The Clerics of Islam: Religious Authority and Political Power in Saudi Arabia |date=2014 |publisher=Yale University Press |page=29 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tOEdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=al-Barbahari+d.941&source=bl&ots=w5XJ37Ctvp&sig=ACfU3U2Sc4h363_31OT3KOeevWq7ETcD-A&hl=en&ppis=_c&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjygP-6g-PoAhXTX80KHYGLCtIQ6AEwAHoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=al-Barbahari%20d.941&f=false |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Under the influence of al-Barbahari and popular pressure of his followers, the [[Caliph]]s [[Al-Muqtadir]] and [[Al-Qahir]] enforced Hanbalism as the state creed, exiling and imprisoning al-Barbahari's enemies and even burying renowned Muslim historian [[Muhammad ibn Jarir al-Tabari]] -- considered a heretic by most Hanbalites at the time -- in secret due to fears of mob violence were a funeral to be held at the public graveyard.<ref name=joel61/>\n\nThe efforts of al-Barbahari and the Baghdad Hanbalites were put to an end in 935 by the new Caliph [[Ar-Radi]]. Al-Barbahari had ordered groups to check any homes suspected of containing wine or musical instruments. The crowds confiscated from shops and physically enforced female entertainers to leave their practices.<ref>Christopher Melchert, ''Studies in Islamic Law and Society'', vol. 4, p. 151. Leiden: Brill Publishers, 1997.</ref> Ar-Radi ended the favored status of the Hanbalites. \n\n==Thought==\nLike other Hanbali, Barbahari strongly opposed ''[[Bid\u02bbah]]'' (religious innovation), defined as anything that the first generation of Muslims, (known as the [[Companions of the Prophet]] or ''Sahabah''), \"did not do\".<ref name=cook-2000-109/> Thus he taught that \"whoever asserts that there is any part of Islam with which the Companions of the Prophet did not provide us has called them [the Companions of the Prophet] liars\".<ref name=cook-2000-109> While opposed to the [[reason]] provided it was put to good use and did not contradict doctrine such as [[God_in_Islam#Attributes|divine attributes]].<ref name=\"Mouline-2014-29\"/> Nonetheless, he wrote,  \"You don't ask 'Why?' and 'How?' Theology, polemic, disputation, and argument are and innovation which casts doubt into the heart\".<ref name=cook-2000-109>Cook, Michael, ''The Koran, a very short introduction, Oxford University Press, 2000, p.109</ref>\n   \n== See also ==\n* [[Islamic scholars]]\n* [[Notable Hanbali Scholars]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Hanbali scholars}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Al-Barbahaaree}}\n[[Category:940 deaths]]\n[[Category:Hanbalis]]\n[[Category:Sunni Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:People from Baghdad]]\n[[Category:Hadith scholars]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Sunni Muslims]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:10th-century people of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:10th-century Arabs]]\n[[Category:10th-century jurists]]\n", "name_user": "BoogaLouie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThought:correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Hasan_ibn_%27Ali_al-Barbahari"}
{"title_page": "Lydia Bourouiba", "text_new": "{{short description|French epidemiologist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Lydia Bourouiba\n| alma_mater        = [[McGill University]]\n| workplaces        = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] <br> [[York University]]\n| thesis_title      = Numerical and theoretical study of homogeneous rotating turbulence\n| thesis_url        = http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/778189413\n| thesis_year       = 2008\n| website           = [http://lbourouiba.mit.edu/ Bourouiba Group]\n}}\n\n'''Lydia Bourouiba''' is a French epidemiologist who is the Esther and Harold E. Edgerton Assistant Professor in the Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]. Her research considers the fluid dynamics of disease transmission. During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Borouiba studied respiratory pathogen emissions and their implications for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease]]. \n\n== Early life and education ==\nBourouiba is from [[France]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lok|first=Corie|date=2016-06-02|title=The snot-spattered experiments that show how far sneezes really spread|url=http://www.nature.com/news/the-snot-spattered-experiments-that-show-how-far-sneezes-really-spread-1.19996|journal=Nature News|language=en|volume=534|issue=7605|pages=24|doi=10.1038/534024a}}</ref> She spent part of her childhood in [[Algeria]], which was in the midst of a [[Algerian Civil War|civil war]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/voices/meet-the-women-of-breakthrough-portraits-of-women-in-science/|title=Meet the Women of Breakthrough: Portraits of Women in Science|last=Driscoll|first=Emily V.|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> This experience motivated Bourouiba to work in public health and epidemiology. She first studied in France before moving to [[Montreal]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2008 she completed her graduate research at [[McGill University]], where she developed a theoretical description of [[turbulence]] fluid flow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://meche.mit.edu/people/faculty/lbouro@mit.edu|title=MECHE PEOPLE: Lydia Bourouiba {{!}} MIT Department of Mechanical Engineering|website=meche.mit.edu|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> After completing her doctorate, Bourouiba joined [[York University]] in [[Canada]]. Here she started to concentrate on coughs and sneezes; \"violent expiratory events\".<ref name=\":0\" /> She believed that rooting her epidemiological studies in physics and fluid mechanics would allow her to understand the spread of emerging infectious diseases, including [[SARS]] and [[Ebola virus disease]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She worked in [[Toronto]] at the Centre for Disease Modelling where she modelled the spread of [[influenza]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://imes.mit.edu/people/faculty/bourouiba-lydia/|title=Lydia Bourouiba|website=Institute for Medical Engineering & Science|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nBourouiba uses mathematical modelling to understand the spread of disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cee.mit.edu/professor-bourouibas-research-on-the-fluid-dynamics-of-disease-transmission-featured-by-nature/|title=Professor Bourouiba's Research on the Fluid Dynamics of Disease Transmission Featured by Nature|last=mituser|date=2016-06-20|website=MIT CEE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> After her early work in the modelling and theoretical aspects of expiratory events, when she joined [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 2010 she became interested in the size distribution of exhaled droplets.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Bourouiba established a new laboratory at Massachusetts Institute of Technology that combines [[fluid dynamics]] with epidemiological modelling.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.mit.edu/2016/sneezing-fluid-cascade-not-simple-spray-0210|title=Sneezing produces complex fluid cascade, not a simple spray|website=MIT News|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> It includes at [[biosafety level]] 2 laboratory, which permits the study of the sneezes of healthy patients as well as those with influenza.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lok|first=Corie|date=2016-06-02|title=The snot-spattered experiments that show how far sneezes really spread|url=http://www.nature.com/news/the-snot-spattered-experiments-that-show-how-far-sneezes-really-spread-1.19996|journal=Nature News|language=en|volume=534|issue=7605|pages=24|doi=10.1038/534024a}}</ref> \n\nIn 2016 Bourouiba used two high-speed video cameras to show the movement of fluid droplets that spread from a sneeze.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.mit.edu/news-clip/clip-nature-snot-spattered-experiments-show-how-far-sneezes-really-spread|title=Clip Nature The snot-spattered experiments that show how far sneezes really spread {{!}} MIT News|website=news.mit.edu|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Bourouiba|first=Lydia|last2=Dehandschoewercker|first2=Eline|last3=Bush|first3=John W. M.|date=2014|title=Violent expiratory events: on coughing and sneezing|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-fluid-mechanics/article/violent-expiratory-events-on-coughing-and-sneezing/475FCFCBD32C7DB6C1E49476DB7A7446|journal=Journal of Fluid Mechanics|language=en|volume=745|pages=537\u2013563|doi=10.1017/jfm.2014.88|issn=0022-1120|via=}}</ref> The cameras were set up to collect thousands of frames per second, and could be studied in slow motion.<ref name=\":0\" /> The high-speed video footage of more than 100 sneezes allowed Bourouiba to analyse the 150 millisecond long moments that a sneeze is expelled into the air.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Bourouiba|first=Lydia|date=2016-08-25|title=A Sneeze|url=http://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMicm1501197|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|language=en|volume=375|issue=8|pages=e15|doi=10.1056/NEJMicm1501197|issn=0028-4793}}</ref>  Her videos showed that sneezes, exhalations and coughs consist of mucosalivary droplets that are primarily made of a multi-phase gas cloud. This gas cloud grows as it moves away from the mouth, drawing in air from the surrounding environment.<ref name=\":0\" /> She showed that the fluid sheet first of droplets balloons, then evolves into long filaments and eventually disperses as a spray of smaller droplets. This complex fluid cascade was not as simple as models that had previously been used to model coughs and sneezes, and showed that droplet spread could be strongly impacted by environmental temperature and humidity.<ref name=\":0\" /> The conditions within the turbulent gas (puff) cloud can extend the lifetime of the enclosed droplets. These turbulent gas clouds were shown to protects the droplets as they move through the air, and the internal climate of the cloud shown to extend the lifetime of the enclosed droplets. Bourouiba demonstrated that exhalation speeds of 10 \u2013 30 ms<sup>-1</sup>, which means that droplets bearing pathogens can travel up to eight metres.<ref name=\":4\" /> Eventually the pathogen bearing droplets within these turbulent clouds evaporate, leaving behind a spray of residue and droplet nuclei.<ref name=\":3\" /> The residues can survive in the air for hours, eventually following the air flow that is imposed by [[climate control]] systems.<ref name=\":3\" /> She believes that this analysis can better inform public health interventions, as well as identifying people who may act as super-spreaders.<ref name=\":2\" /> Her research on sneezes formed the basis of educational materials produced by [[Science Friday]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencefriday.com/educational-resources/snotty-plots-how-do-you-graph-a-sneeze/|title=Snotty Plots: How Do You Graph A Sneeze?|last=Zych|first=Ariel|website=Science Friday|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] Bourouiba looked to understand how her models of sneezes could help to understand and slow the spread of [[SARS-CoV-2]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Bourouiba|first=Lydia|date=2020-03-26|title=Turbulent Gas Clouds and Respiratory Pathogen Emissions: Potential Implications for Reducing Transmission of COVID-19|url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2763852|journal=JAMA|language=en|doi=10.1001/jama.2020.4756}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://podcasts.google.com/?feed=aHR0cDovL2JhY2t0cmFja3MuZm0vanVzdGh1bWFuL2VwaWRlbWljLXdpdGgtZHItY2VsaW5lLWdvdW5kZXItYW5kLXJvbi1rbGFpbi9mZWVk&episode=M2NkOTliNjItNmFjNy0xMWVhLWI0ZGQtMGUxZWJiMWJhOTNm|title=EPIDEMIC with Dr. Celine Gounder and Ronald Klain - BONUS / A False Dichotomy: Airborne versus Droplet / Roxanne Khamsi and Lydia Bourouiba|last=PRODUCTIONS|first=JUST HUMAN|website=Google Podcasts|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Early reports from [[China]] indicated that particles of the virus were found in the hospital rooms of patients with the disease.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ong|first=Sean Wei Xiang|last2=Tan|first2=Yian Kim|last3=Chia|first3=Po Ying|last4=Lee|first4=Tau Hong|last5=Ng|first5=Oon Tek|last6=Wong|first6=Michelle Su Yen|last7=Marimuthu|first7=Kalisvar|date=2020-03-04|title=Air, Surface Environmental, and Personal Protective Equipment Contamination by Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) From a Symptomatic Patient|url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2762692|journal=JAMA|language=en|doi=10.1001/jama.2020.3227}}</ref> She has argued that the guidance given by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) and [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|Centers for Disease Control]] (CDC) may underestimate the distance as they do not take into account the dynamics of the turbulent puff cloud.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/they-say-coronavirus-isnt-airborne-but-its-definitely-borne-by-air/|title=They Say Coronavirus Isn't Airborne\u2014but It's Definitely Borne by Air|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biotecnika.org/2020/04/distance-coronavirus-can-travel-in-air-could-be-27-feet/|title=Distance Coronavirus Can Travel In Air Could Be 27 Feet|last=Thampi|first=Namitha|date=2020-04-01|website=BioTecNika|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> She has looked to understand the efficacy of [[face masks during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lbourouiba.mit.edu/MITBourouibaCOVID19|title=MIT Bourouiba COVID-19 {{!}} Bourouiba Group|website=lbourouiba.mit.edu|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/04/coronavirus-pandemic-airborne-go-outside-masks/609235/|title=Everyone Thinks They\u2019re Right About Masks|last=Yong|first=Ed|date=2020-04-01|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n*{{Cite journal|last=Weitz|first=Joshua S|last2=Stock|first2=Charles A|last3=Wilhelm|first3=Steven W|last4=Bourouiba|first4=Lydia|last5=Coleman|first5=Maureen L|last6=Buchan|first6=Alison|last7=Follows|first7=Michael J|last8=Fuhrman|first8=Jed A|last9=Jover|first9=Luis F|last10=Lennon|first10=Jay T|last11=Middelboe|first11=Mathias|date=2015-01-30|title=A multitrophic model to quantify the effects of marine viruses on microbial food webs and ecosystem processes|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1038/ismej.2014.220|journal=The ISME Journal|volume=9|issue=6|pages=1352\u20131364|doi=10.1038/ismej.2014.220|issn=1751-7362}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Bourouiba|first=Lydia|last2=Dehandschoewercker|first2=Eline|last3=Bush|first3=John W. M.|date=2014|title=Violent expiratory events: on coughing and sneezing|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-fluid-mechanics/article/violent-expiratory-events-on-coughing-and-sneezing/475FCFCBD32C7DB6C1E49476DB7A7446|journal=Journal of Fluid Mechanics|language=en|volume=745|pages=537\u2013563|doi=10.1017/jfm.2014.88|issn=0022-1120|via=}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=BOUROUIBA|first=LYDIA|last2=BARTELLO|first2=PETER|date=2007-08-31|title=The intermediate Rossby number range and two-dimensional\u2013three-dimensional transfers in rotating decaying homogeneous turbulence|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1017/s0022112007007124|journal=Journal of Fluid Mechanics|volume=587|pages=139\u2013161|doi=10.1017/s0022112007007124|issn=0022-1120}}\n\n== Personal life ==\nAlongside her research, Bourouiba takes part in mountain climbing and long bicycle rides.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bourouiba, Lydia}}\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:French epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Coronavirus researchers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French epidemiologist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Lydia Bourouiba\n| alma_mater        = [[McGill University]]\n| workplaces        = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] <br> [[York University]]\n| thesis_title      = Numerical and theoretical study of homogeneous rotating turbulence\n| thesis_url        = http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/778189413\n| thesis_year       = 2008\n| website           = [http://lbourouiba.mit.edu/ Bourouiba Group]\n}}\n\n'''Lydia Bourouiba''' is a French epidemiologist who is the Esther and Harold E. Edgerton Assistant Professor in the Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]. Her research considers the fluid dynamics of disease transmission. During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Borouiba studied respiratory pathogen emissions and their implications for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease]]. \n\n== Early life and education ==\nBourouiba is from [[France]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lok|first=Corie|date=2016-06-02|title=The snot-spattered experiments that show how far sneezes really spread|url=http://www.nature.com/news/the-snot-spattered-experiments-that-show-how-far-sneezes-really-spread-1.19996|journal=Nature News|language=en|volume=534|issue=7605|pages=24|doi=10.1038/534024a}}</ref> She spent part of her childhood in [[Algeria]], which was in the midst of a [[Algerian Civil War|civil war]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/voices/meet-the-women-of-breakthrough-portraits-of-women-in-science/|title=Meet the Women of Breakthrough: Portraits of Women in Science|last=Driscoll|first=Emily V.|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> This experience motivated Bourouiba to work in public health and epidemiology. She first studied in France before moving to [[Montreal]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2008 she completed her graduate research at [[McGill University]], where she developed a theoretical description of [[turbulence]] fluid flow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://meche.mit.edu/people/faculty/lbouro@mit.edu|title=MECHE PEOPLE: Lydia Bourouiba {{!}} MIT Department of Mechanical Engineering|website=meche.mit.edu|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> After completing her doctorate, Bourouiba joined [[York University]] in [[Canada]]. Here she started to concentrate on coughs and sneezes; \"violent expiratory events\".<ref name=\":0\" /> She believed that rooting her epidemiological studies in physics and fluid mechanics would allow her to understand the spread of emerging infectious diseases, including [[SARS]] and [[Ebola virus disease]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She worked in [[Toronto]] at the Centre for Disease Modelling where she modelled the spread of [[influenza]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://imes.mit.edu/people/faculty/bourouiba-lydia/|title=Lydia Bourouiba|website=Institute for Medical Engineering & Science|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nBourouiba uses mathematical modelling to understand the spread of disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cee.mit.edu/professor-bourouibas-research-on-the-fluid-dynamics-of-disease-transmission-featured-by-nature/|title=Professor Bourouiba's Research on the Fluid Dynamics of Disease Transmission Featured by Nature|last=mituser|date=2016-06-20|website=MIT CEE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> After her early work in the modelling and theoretical aspects of expiratory events, when she joined [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 2010 she became interested in the size distribution of exhaled droplets.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Bourouiba established a new laboratory at Massachusetts Institute of Technology that combines [[fluid dynamics]] with epidemiological modelling.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.mit.edu/2016/sneezing-fluid-cascade-not-simple-spray-0210|title=Sneezing produces complex fluid cascade, not a simple spray|website=MIT News|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> It includes at [[biosafety level]] 2 laboratory, which permits the study of the sneezes of healthy patients as well as those with influenza.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lok|first=Corie|date=2016-06-02|title=The snot-spattered experiments that show how far sneezes really spread|url=http://www.nature.com/news/the-snot-spattered-experiments-that-show-how-far-sneezes-really-spread-1.19996|journal=Nature News|language=en|volume=534|issue=7605|pages=24|doi=10.1038/534024a}}</ref> \n\nIn 2016 Bourouiba used two high-speed video cameras to show the movement of fluid droplets that spread from a sneeze.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.mit.edu/news-clip/clip-nature-snot-spattered-experiments-show-how-far-sneezes-really-spread|title=Clip Nature The snot-spattered experiments that show how far sneezes really spread {{!}} MIT News|website=news.mit.edu|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Bourouiba|first=Lydia|last2=Dehandschoewercker|first2=Eline|last3=Bush|first3=John W. M.|date=2014|title=Violent expiratory events: on coughing and sneezing|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-fluid-mechanics/article/violent-expiratory-events-on-coughing-and-sneezing/475FCFCBD32C7DB6C1E49476DB7A7446|journal=Journal of Fluid Mechanics|language=en|volume=745|pages=537\u2013563|doi=10.1017/jfm.2014.88|issn=0022-1120|via=}}</ref> The cameras were set up to collect thousands of frames per second, and could be studied in slow motion.<ref name=\":0\" /> The high-speed video footage of more than 100 sneezes allowed Bourouiba to analyse the 150 millisecond long moments that a sneeze is expelled into the air.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Bourouiba|first=Lydia|date=2016-08-25|title=A Sneeze|url=http://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMicm1501197|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|language=en|volume=375|issue=8|pages=e15|doi=10.1056/NEJMicm1501197|issn=0028-4793}}</ref>  Her videos showed that sneezes, exhalations and coughs consist of mucosalivary droplets that are primarily made of a multi-phase gas cloud. This gas cloud grows as it moves away from the mouth, drawing in air from the surrounding environment.<ref name=\":0\" /> She showed that the fluid sheet first of droplets balloons, then evolves into long filaments and eventually disperses as a spray of smaller droplets. This complex fluid cascade was not as simple as models that had previously been used to model coughs and sneezes, and showed that droplet spread could be strongly impacted by environmental temperature and humidity.<ref name=\":0\" /> The conditions within the turbulent gas (puff) cloud can extend the lifetime of the enclosed droplets. These turbulent gas clouds were shown to protects the droplets as they move through the air, and the internal climate of the cloud shown to extend the lifetime of the enclosed droplets. Bourouiba demonstrated that exhalation speeds of 10 \u2013 30 ms<sup>-1</sup>, which means that droplets bearing pathogens can travel up to eight metres.<ref name=\":4\" /> Eventually the pathogen bearing droplets within these turbulent clouds evaporate, leaving behind a spray of residue and droplet nuclei.<ref name=\":3\" /> The residues can survive in the air for hours, eventually following the air flow that is imposed by [[climate control]] systems.<ref name=\":3\" /> She believes that this analysis can better inform public health interventions, as well as identifying people who may act as super-spreaders.<ref name=\":2\" /> Her research on sneezes formed the basis of educational materials produced by [[Science Friday]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencefriday.com/educational-resources/snotty-plots-how-do-you-graph-a-sneeze/|title=Snotty Plots: How Do You Graph A Sneeze?|last=Zych|first=Ariel|website=Science Friday|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] Bourouiba looked to understand how her models of sneezes could help to understand and slow the spread of [[SARS-CoV-2]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Bourouiba|first=Lydia|date=2020-03-26|title=Turbulent Gas Clouds and Respiratory Pathogen Emissions: Potential Implications for Reducing Transmission of COVID-19|url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2763852|journal=JAMA|language=en|doi=10.1001/jama.2020.4756}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://podcasts.google.com/?feed=aHR0cDovL2JhY2t0cmFja3MuZm0vanVzdGh1bWFuL2VwaWRlbWljLXdpdGgtZHItY2VsaW5lLWdvdW5kZXItYW5kLXJvbi1rbGFpbi9mZWVk&episode=M2NkOTliNjItNmFjNy0xMWVhLWI0ZGQtMGUxZWJiMWJhOTNm|title=EPIDEMIC with Dr. Celine Gounder and Ronald Klain - BONUS / A False Dichotomy: Airborne versus Droplet / Roxanne Khamsi and Lydia Bourouiba|last=PRODUCTIONS|first=JUST HUMAN|website=Google Podcasts|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Early reports from [[China]] indicated that particles of the virus were found in the hospital rooms of patients with the disease.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ong|first=Sean Wei Xiang|last2=Tan|first2=Yian Kim|last3=Chia|first3=Po Ying|last4=Lee|first4=Tau Hong|last5=Ng|first5=Oon Tek|last6=Wong|first6=Michelle Su Yen|last7=Marimuthu|first7=Kalisvar|date=2020-03-04|title=Air, Surface Environmental, and Personal Protective Equipment Contamination by Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) From a Symptomatic Patient|url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2762692|journal=JAMA|language=en|doi=10.1001/jama.2020.3227}}</ref> She has argued that the guidance given by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) and [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|Centers for Disease Control]] (CDC) may underestimate the distance as they do not take into account the dynamics of the turbulent puff cloud.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/they-say-coronavirus-isnt-airborne-but-its-definitely-borne-by-air/|title=They Say Coronavirus Isn't Airborne\u2014but It's Definitely Borne by Air|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biotecnika.org/2020/04/distance-coronavirus-can-travel-in-air-could-be-27-feet/|title=Distance Coronavirus Can Travel In Air Could Be 27 Feet|last=Thampi|first=Namitha|date=2020-04-01|website=BioTecNika|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> She has looked to understand the efficacy of [[face masks during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lbourouiba.mit.edu/MITBourouibaCOVID19|title=MIT Bourouiba COVID-19 {{!}} Bourouiba Group|website=lbourouiba.mit.edu|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/04/coronavirus-pandemic-airborne-go-outside-masks/609235/|title=Everyone Thinks They\u2019re Right About Masks|last=Yong|first=Ed|date=2020-04-01|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n*{{Cite journal|last=Weitz|first=Joshua S|last2=Stock|first2=Charles A|last3=Wilhelm|first3=Steven W|last4=Bourouiba|first4=Lydia|last5=Coleman|first5=Maureen L|last6=Buchan|first6=Alison|last7=Follows|first7=Michael J|last8=Fuhrman|first8=Jed A|last9=Jover|first9=Luis F|last10=Lennon|first10=Jay T|last11=Middelboe|first11=Mathias|date=2015-01-30|title=A multitrophic model to quantify the effects of marine viruses on microbial food webs and ecosystem processes|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1038/ismej.2014.220|journal=The ISME Journal|volume=9|issue=6|pages=1352\u20131364|doi=10.1038/ismej.2014.220|issn=1751-7362}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Bourouiba|first=Lydia|last2=Dehandschoewercker|first2=Eline|last3=Bush|first3=John W. M.|date=2014|title=Violent expiratory events: on coughing and sneezing|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-fluid-mechanics/article/violent-expiratory-events-on-coughing-and-sneezing/475FCFCBD32C7DB6C1E49476DB7A7446|journal=Journal of Fluid Mechanics|language=en|volume=745|pages=537\u2013563|doi=10.1017/jfm.2014.88|issn=0022-1120|via=}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=BOUROUIBA|first=LYDIA|last2=BARTELLO|first2=PETER|date=2007-08-31|title=The intermediate Rossby number range and two-dimensional\u2013three-dimensional transfers in rotating decaying homogeneous turbulence|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1017/s0022112007007124|journal=Journal of Fluid Mechanics|volume=587|pages=139\u2013161|doi=10.1017/s0022112007007124|issn=0022-1120}}\n\n== Personal life ==\nAlongside her research, Bourouiba takes part in mountain climbing and long bicycle rides.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== References ==\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bourouiba, Lydia}}\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:French epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Coronavirus researchers]]\n", "name_user": "Kj cheetham", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/