{"title_page": "Oasis Academy Coulsdon", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Oasis Academy Coulsdon\n | image                   = OA_Coulsdon_Logo.png\n | image_size              = \n | coordinates             = {{coord|51.29912|-0.11075|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n | motto                   = Excellence through rigour, resilience and passion\n | established             = 1 September 2008\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n | president               = \n | head                    = Andrew Booth<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.oasisacademycoulsdon.org/aboutus/contacts/ | title = Contacts | publisher = Oasis Academy Coulsdon | accessdate = 30 November 2009}}</ref>, Catrin Green\n | head_label              = Principal\n | r_head_label            = \n | r_head                  = \n | chair_label             = \n | chair                   = \n | founder                 = [[Steve Chalke]], [[Oasis Trust]]\n | specialist              = [[Technology College]], Business and Enterprise\n | address                 = Homefield Road\n | city                    = [[Coulsdon]]\n | county                  = [[Greater London]]\n | country                 = England\n | postcode                = CR5 1ES\n | local_authority         = [[Croydon]]\n | ofsted                  = yes\n | urn                     = 135654\n | staff                   = \n | gender                  = [[Coeducational]]\n | lower_age               = 11\n | upper_age               = 16\n | houses                  = Einstein, Owens, Keller, Churchill\n | colours                 = Green {{color box|Lime}} Blue {{color box|midnightBlue}}\n | publication             = \n | free_label_1            = \n | free_1                  = \n | free_label_2            = \n | free_2                  = \n | free_label_3            = \n | free_3                  = \n | website                 = http://www.oasisacademycoulsdon.org/\n}}Currentley - CLOSED\n\n'''Oasis Academy Coulsdon''', formerly known as '''Coulsdon High School''', is a [[school]] in the [[London Borough of Croydon]], [[England]]. It is between the area of [[Coulsdon]] and [[Caterham]]. It is an [[Academy (English school)|academy]] run by the Christian [[Charitable organization|charity]] [[Oasis Trust]].  The conversion to an academy in 2008 attracted a \u00a320 million investment over five years by the [[UK Government|government]], via the Oasis Trust.<ref name=AcademyDecision>{{cite web|title=Delegated decision made by the Chief Executive: award of contract for the redevelopment of Coulsdon Academy|url=http://www.croydon.gov.uk/contents/documents/meetings/546596/910708/2010-06-14/coulsdonacademy.pdf|work=Croydon Council Website|publisher=Croydon Council|accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=croydon/>\n== History ==\n\n=== Taunton Manor ===\nTaunton Manor opened in 1959. The main buildings have stayed pretty much the same since then, with various extensions being built.\n\n=== Coulsdon High ===\nTaunton Manor reopened as ''Coulsdon High'' in the Summer of 1994. Several new extensions were built for the changeover. In 1999 the school, which was located in an area where some other schools were selective,<ref name=ElevenPlusRegions>{{cite web|title=11 Plus Regions|url=http://www.elevenplusexams.co.uk/schools/regions|website=Eleven Plus Exams|publisher=Eleven Plus Exams|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> attempted to change its admissions policy to achieve \"a more balanced ability range\", but was prevented from doing so.<ref name=OSA1999>{{cite web|title=OSA Determination ADA/00014|url=http://www.schoolsadjudicator.gov.uk/upload/ADA000014_-_Coulsdon.doc|archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110218204125/http://www.schoolsadjudicator.gov.uk/upload/ADA000014_-_Coulsdon.doc|url-status = dead|archive-date=18 February 2011|website=National Archives|publisher=Office of the Schools Adjudicator|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> A further judgement the following year allowed it to retain its feeder primary schools.<ref name=OSA2000>{{cite web|title=OSA Judgement ADA/000210|url=http://www.schoolsadjudicator.gov.uk/upload/ADA000210_-_Coulsdon.doc|archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110218204125/http://www.schoolsadjudicator.gov.uk/upload/ADA000210_-_Coulsdon.doc|url-status = dead|archive-date=18 February 2011|website=National Archives|publisher=Office of the schools adjudicator|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nCoulsdon High received a 'Good' [[Ofsted]] judgement in 2001,<ref name=Ofsted2001>{{cite news|title=A glowing Ofsted report for Coulsdon High School|url=http://www.croydonguardian.co.uk/news/8909.A_glowing_Ofsted_report_for_Coulsdon_High_School/|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=Croydon Guardian|date=2 May 2001}}</ref> and was awarded specialist status for maths, science, IT and design technology in 2002.<ref name=SpecialistStatus>{{cite web|title=High achievers rewarded|url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/49714.print/|website=Richmond & Twickenham Times|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 the school was reported to be suffering significant financial challenge, with an impending budget deficit that was set to impact the school timetable and staffing levels.<ref name=ShortWeekTalks>{{cite news|last1=Menhinnitt|first1=Daniel|title=Talks to stop short week|url=http://www.thisislocallondon.co.uk/news/education/390919.display/|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=This is Local London}}</ref><ref name=DeficitLGCArticle>{{cite news|title=CROYDON LBC UNDERWRITES DEFICIT BUDGETS TO FORESTALL SHORT SCHOOL WEEKS|url=http://www.lgcplus.com/croydon-lbc-underwrites-deficit-budgets-to-forestall-short-school-weeks/1261854.article|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=Local Government Chronicle|date=10 July 2003}}</ref> The problems were linked to a national school funding crisis.<ref name=EveStandFundingCrisis>{{cite news|last1=MILES|first1=TIM|title=720 Children Sent Home as a School's Money Runs Out|url=https://www.questia.com/newspaper/1G1-102118243/720-children-sent-home-as-a-school-s-money-runs-out|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=Evening Standard}}</ref><ref name=CroydonGuardianJune2003>{{cite news|last1=Menhinnitt|first1=Daniel|title=100 school jobs axed|url=http://www.croydonguardian.co.uk/archive/2003/06/12/377842.100_school_jobs_axed/|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=Croydon Guardian|date=12 June 2003}}</ref><ref name=TESFundingCrisis>{{cite news|last1=Slater|first1=Jon|title=Fury at union's 'crass gesture' over crisis|url=https://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storycode=381691|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=Times Educational Supplement|date=4 July 2003}}</ref>\n\n[[Ofsted#School inspections|Ofsted's system of inspection]] changed significantly in 2005, and in 2006 Coulsdon High was put into [[Ofsted#Special measures|Special Measures]]. However a few months later it received its best ever SATS results,<ref name=bestSATS>{{cite web|title=\u2018Failing\u2019 school scores best ever Sats results|url=http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/822027.failing_school_scores_best_ever_sats_results/|work=Your Local Guardian|accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref> and the following year the special measures were revoked by Ofsted when the school was judged to be rapidly improving.<ref name=Ofsted2007>{{cite web|title=Coulsdon High School : 2007 Ofsted Report|url=http://www.educationadviser.co.uk/ofsted-report/coulsdon-high-school-0|work=educationadviser.co.uk|accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref>  The report praised the vision and commitment of the headteacher and senior management team as crucial in setting the agenda for improvement, and also found the school to be in the top 25 per cent of schools for the value it added to students' achievements.\n\nHowever plans to replace Coulsdon High with a sponsored academy were already under way on the grounds that the period in special measures had affected pupil recruitment and created doubt that the school could recover the confidence of local parents quickly enough for financial viability to be restored.<ref name=CabinetPaper>{{cite web|title=THE FUTURE OF COULSDON HIGH SCHOOL|url=https://www.croydon.gov.uk/sites/default/files/articles/downloads/coulsdonhigh.pdf|website=London Borough of Croydon|publisher=London Borough of Croydon|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=AcademyNews>{{cite news|last1=Moody|first1=Graham|title=Christian charity to run Coulsdon academy|url=http://www.croydonguardian.co.uk/news/1686417.Christian_charity_to_run_Coulsdon_academy/|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=Croydon Guardian|date=14 September 2007}}</ref><ref name=ParentConsultation>{{cite web|title=Consultation meeting for parents at Coulsdon High School|url=https://www.croydon.gov.uk/sites/default/files/articles/downloads/coulsdonappendsec3.pdf|website=Croydon Council|publisher=Croydon Council|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=ConsultationResults>{{cite web|title=Coulsdon High Consultation (Results)|url=https://www.croydon.gov.uk/sites/default/files/articles/downloads/coulsdoncon.pdf|website=Croydon.gov.uk|publisher=Croydon Council|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>  Many objected to the plans, claiming that the consultation was flawed and highlighting the school's recent rapid progress.<ref name=flawedConsultation>{{cite web|title=GREEN PARTY SLAMS FLAWED CITY ACADEMY CONSULTATION|url=http://croydongreens.blogspot.co.uk/2008/02/green-party-slams-flawed-city-academy.html|work=croydongreens.blogspot.co.uk|accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=BBCAcademyStory>{{cite web|title=New Academy is 'good for the community'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/london/content/articles/2008/08/18/croydon_oasis_academy_feature.shtml|work=BBC Website|accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=City Academies letter sent to the papers|url=http://croydongreens.blogspot.co.uk/2007/09/city-academies-letter-sent-to-papers.html|work=croydongreens.blogspot.co.uk|accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Miller|first=Harry|title=Exclusive: Chalke outlines plans for new Coulsdon academy|url=http://www.croydonguardian.co.uk/news/2038965.Exclusive__Chalke_outlines_plans_for_new_Coulsdon_academy/|work=Croydon Guardian|accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref>   In its final year Coulsdon High achieved the best [[GCSE]] results in the school's history, a 41% A* - C pass rate.<ref name=croydon/>\n\nCoulsdon Academy closed in July 2007, and the occasion was marked with a party, attended by former staff and students.<ref name=FarewellParty>{{cite news|title=Coulsdon High says goodbye|url=http://www.croydonadvertiser.co.uk/Coulsdon-High-says-goodbye/story-11359888-detail/story.html|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=Croydon Advertiser|date=18 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Oasis Academy Coulsdon ===\nThe school reopened again as ''Oasis Academy Coulsdon'' on 1 September 2008. The opening ceremony was attended by the then [[Secretary of State for Children, Schools and Families|Parliamentary Under Secretary of Schools]] [[Lord Adonis]] and the founder of the Oasis Trust [[Steve Chalke]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/coulsdon/Government-minister-visits-Coulsdon-academy/article-319787-detail/article.html|title=Government minister visits Coulsdon academy}}</ref> The new headteacher was John Murphy.<ref name=croydon>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/latestnews/change-Coulsdon-s-newest-school/article-303334-detail/article.html|title=All change at Coulsdon's newest school}}</ref> Oasis invested over \u00a320 million of government funding into the school, resulting in the opening of a community [[health-care]] centre in 2009 and a [[sixth form]] in 2011.<ref name=croydon/> In July 2014 the Sixth Form shut down due to poor intake.<ref name=SixthForm2014>{{cite news|last1=Millard|first1=Rachel|title=Sixth form at Oasis Academy Coulsdon is closed after two years|url=http://www.croydonadvertiser.co.uk/School-s-sixth-form-closed-years/story-20942192-detail/story.html|accessdate=26 June 2015|work=Croydon & Purley Advertiser|date=13 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe academy was rated as \"good\" by Ofsted in its first full inspection in 2011,<ref name=Ofsted2011>{{cite web|last1=Salaria|first1=Kekshan|title=Oasis Academy Coulsdon: Inspection Report|url=http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/provider/files/1970269/urn/135654.pdf|website=Ofsted|publisher=Ofsted|accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref> and it maintained that rating under the [[Ofsted#Current system of inspection|revised Ofsted framework]] in 2015.<ref name=Ofsted2015>{{cite web|last1=King|first1=Chris|title=Oasis Academy Coulsdon: Inspection Report|url=http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/provider/files/2465609/urn/135654.pdf|website=Ofsted|publisher=Ofsted|accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, the school closed early for the academic year because of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|that year's Coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oasisacademycoulsdon.org/academy-life/academy-closure-covid-19|title=Academy Closure- Covid-19 -|website=www.oasisacademycoulsdon.org|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Famous graduates ==\nFamous graduates of Oasis Academy Coulsdon in all its previous forms,  the three times world champion [[boxing|boxer]] [[Duke McKenzie]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishboxing.net/news_553-Boxer-of-the-Past-Duke-McKenzie.html|title=Boxers of the past- Duke McKenzie|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927222940/http://www.britishboxing.net/news_553-Boxer-of-the-Past-Duke-McKenzie.html|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Mazhar Majeed]], the cricket bookmaker who was arrested on charges of match fixing, is also a graduate.\n\n== Safety & Security ==\nOasis Academy Coulsdon contains an advanced security system using Salto Inspired Access<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saltosystems.com/en/|title=SALTO Systems - Home|website=SALTO Systems|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> to secure and control doors around the premises. All classroom are always locked from the outside and has a fully integrated lockdown system allowing the school to remain secure during a threat. All areas of the building have fire sprinklers built into the ceiling and fire extinguishers placed strategically around the building. The building is protected from fire with an addressable digital Protec<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.protec.co.uk/|title=Protec Fire & Security|website=www.protec.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> fire alarm system installed. There are over 100 CCTV cameras installed and DMR Digital radios are used to ensure secure communication.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.oasisacademycoulsdon.org/ Oasis Academy Coulsdon]\n\n{{Schools in Croydon}}\n{{Oasis Academies}}\n\n[[Category:Oasis Academies|Coulsdon]]\n[[Category:Academies in the London Borough of Croydon]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in the London Borough of Croydon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Oasis Academy Coulsdon\n | image                   = OA_Coulsdon_Logo.png\n | image_size              = \n | coordinates             = {{coord|51.29912|-0.11075|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n | motto                   = Excellence through rigour, resilience and passion\n | established             = 1 September 2008\n | closed                  = 20th March 2020 - Coronavirus\n | type                    = [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n | president               = \n | head                    = Andrew Booth<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.oasisacademycoulsdon.org/aboutus/contacts/ | title = Contacts | publisher = Oasis Academy Coulsdon | accessdate = 30 November 2009}}</re