icon|USA}} [[Chrysler]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22.8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|22.8|1995}}\n| Tracinda led by [[Kirk Kerkorian]] was unable to come up with the financing in order to complete the deal. Chrysler was able to leverage its relationships with investment banks to block Kerkorian from being able to get the money necessary for the takeover.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1995/06/01/kerkorian-withdraws-bid-to-acquire-chrysler-corp/a511c4bd-c437-43a0-a2e8-24a57095f2de/</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 85\n| 1996\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[British Telecom]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[MCI Inc.]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|22|1996}}\n| British Telecom held a partial stake in MCI since 1994 and was looking to acquire the entirety of it. [[Worldcom]] ended up winning the takeover fight with a $37 billion bid..<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/02/business/a-british-company-weighs-buying-mci-in-22-billion-deal.html</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 86\n| 2020\n| {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Seven & i Holdings]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Marathon Petroleum]] <small>([[Speedway LLC]])</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|22|2020}}\n| Seven & i walked away from the potential deal, citing concerns over the price.<ref>https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-speedway-m-a-seven-i-hldgs/japans-seven-i-abandons-22-billion-bid-for-speedway-gas-stations-in-u-s-source-idUKKBN20S11A</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 87\n| 1989\n| {{flagicon|FRA}}{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Sir James Goldsmith]] <br/> {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Jacob Rothschild, 4th Baron Rothschild]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Kerry Packer]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[British American Tobacco]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|21.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|21|1989}}\n| British American Tobacco rejected the deal as it planned to break up the conglomerate which the company\u2019s chairman [[Patrick Sheehy]] described as \u201cmost disadvantageous to the company, its shareholders, customers, policyholders and employees.\u201d<ref>https://apnews.com/f1f3500b28b47db7883e6adead6633ab</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 88\n| 2017\n| {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Clariant]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Huntsman Corporation|Huntsman]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|20.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|20|2017}}\n| After months of pressure from activist investors, the companies announced they would abandon their merger plans, with investors citing a reduction in shareholder value as the cause.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-clariant-huntsman-statement/activist-investors-scupper-20-billion-clariant-huntsman-merger-idUKKBN1CW0RI|title=Activist investors scupper $20 billion Clariant-Huntsman merger|first=John Miller and Oliver|last=Hirt|website=reuters.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119012937/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-clariant-huntsman-statement/activist-investors-scupper-20-billion-clariant-huntsman-merger-idUKKBN1CW0RI|archive-date=19 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of largest companies by revenue]]\n* [[List of largest employers]]\n* [[List of companies by profit and loss]]\n* [[List of public corporations by market capitalization]]\n* [[List of largest pharmaceutical mergers and acquisitions]]\n* [[List of largest corporate spin-offs]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=N|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Corporate finance and investment banking|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of corporate acquisitions|Largest mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Mergers and acquisitions|.]]\n[[Category:Corporation-related lists|Largest mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Economy-related lists of superlatives|Mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "Cigarandawaffle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLargest ever deals which have failed to complete", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_largest_mergers_and_acquisitions"}
{"title_page": "Mike Scarry", "text_new": "{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=Michael Scarry\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=\n|number=20\n|position=[[Center (American football)|Center]], [[Tackle (American football)|Tackle]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1920|2|1}}\n|birth_place=[[Duquesne, Pennsylvania]]\n|death_date= {{death date and age|2012|9|9|1920|2|1}}\n|death_place=[[Fort Myers, Florida]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=0\n|weight_lbs=214\n|high_school=[[Duquesne High School|Duquesne (PA)]]\n|college=[[Waynesburg Yellow Jackets football|Waynesburg College]]\n|pastteams=\n* [[Cleveland Rams]] ({{NFL Year|1944}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1945}})\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ([[All-America Football Conference#1946|1946]]\u2013[[All-America Football Conference#1947|1947]])\n|pastcoaching=\n* [[Case Western Reserve Spartans football|Western Reserve]] ([[Head coach|HC]]) [[1948 college football season|1948]]\u2013[[1949 college football season|1949]]\n* [[Santa Clara Broncos football|Santa Clara University]] (Asst.) [[1950 college football season|1950]]\u2013[[1951 college football season|1951]]\n* [[Loras Duhawks football|Loras College]] ([[Head coach|HC]]) [[1952 college football season|1952]]\u2013[[1953 college football season|1953]]\n* [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington State University]] (Asst.) [[1954 college football season|1954]]\u2013[[1955 college football season|1955]]\n* [[University of Cincinnati]] ([[American football positions#Defensive line|DL]]) [[1956 college football season|1956]]\u2013[[1962 college football season|1962]]\n* [[Waynesburg Yellow Jackets|Waynesburg College]] ([[Head coach|HC]]) [[1963 college football season|1963]]\u2013[[1965 college football season|1965]]\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ([[American football positions#Defensive line|DL]]) {{NFL Year|1966}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1968}}\n* Scout, various teams {{NFL Year|1969}}\n* [[Miami Dolphins]] ([[American football positions#Defensive line|DL]]) {{NFL Year|1970}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1985}}\n|highlights=\n* [[NFL Championship|NFL Champion]] ([[1945 NFL Championship Game|1945]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[All-America Football Conference|AAFC Champion]] ([[All-America Football Conference#1946|1946]], [[All-America Football Conference#1947|1947]])\n* Member, Pennsylvania Sports Hall of Fame\n|statseason=1947\n|statlabel1=Games\n|statvalue1=45\n|statlabel2=Interceptions\n|statvalue2=7\n|nflnew=mikescarry/2524996\n|pfr=ScarMi20\n}}\n\n'''Michael Joseph Scarry''' (February 1, 1920 \u2013 September 9, 2012) was an [[American football]] player and coach. He grew up in [[Pennsylvania]] and was a star on his high school basketball team. Scarry played football in college at [[Waynesburg University|Waynesburg College]] in [[Waynesburg, Pennsylvania]] and went on to join the [[Cleveland Rams]] in the [[National Football League]] as a [[center (American football)|center]] following a stint in the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] during [[World War II]]. The Rams moved to Los Angeles after winning the [[1945 NFL Championship Game|1945 NFL championship]], and Scarry elected to stay in Cleveland and play for the [[Cleveland Browns]] under coach [[Paul Brown]] in the new [[All-America Football Conference]]. The Browns won the AAFC championship in 1946 and 1947 while Scarry was on the team.\n\nScarry, who coached the basketball team at [[Case Western Reserve University|Western Reserve University]] in Cleveland during his playing career, retired from pro football after the 1947 season to take up a post as head coach of the school's football team. He stayed there for two seasons before moving to [[Santa Clara University]] in [[California]] as an assistant coach. Scarry then moved in 1952 to [[Loras College]] in [[Iowa]] as an assistant. After a stint at [[Washington State University]], he spent six years as the line coach for the [[University of Cincinnati]]. Scarry served as head football coach at Waynesburg, his alma mater, for three seasons between 1963 and 1965. He got his first professional coaching job in 1966 with the NFL's [[Washington Redskins]], the following year, and became the defensive line coach of the [[Miami Dolphins]] three years later. He stayed with the Dolphins for 15 seasons until his retirement; during his Dolphins career, the team won two [[Super Bowl]]s. Scarry was inducted into the Pennsylvania Sports Hall of Fame in 2000.\n\n==High school, college and military service==\n\nScarry grew up in [[Duquesne, Pennsylvania]], where he was a star on his high school basketball team.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\" /> He also played football, but was not a standout.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\" /> Scarry attended [[Waynesburg University|Waynesburg College]], a small school in [[Waynesburg, Pennsylvania]], where he continued to play football and basketball.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\" /><ref name=\"Scarry joins Rams\">{{cite news|title=Rams Need Strengthening at End and Tackle Posts|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=August 27, 1944|page=2C}}</ref><ref name=\"Scarry in PD\">{{cite news|title=Raging Ram Rookie|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=November 12, 1944|page=2C|quote=Mike Scarry, 210-pound center of the Cleveland Rams who played his collegiate football at Waynesburg and hails from Duquesne, Pa. ... Mike rates as one of the rookie finds of the year.}}</ref> He served in the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] during [[World War II]] in [[North Africa]], but came down with asthma and was given a medical discharge.<ref name=\"Scarry considered at Reserve\" /> He signed with the [[Cleveland Rams]] of the [[National Football League]] starting in 1944.<ref name=\"Scarry joins Rams\" />\n\n==Professional career==\n\nScarry began the 1944 season with the Rams at left tackle, but was shifted to center in September.<ref name=\"Scarry shifted to center\">{{cite news|last=Dietrich|first=John|title=Conkright Will Be Regular End For Ram Eleven|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 12, 1944|page=13|quote=Mike Scarry, the Rams' rookie tackle from Waynesburg, also has been changed to center.}}</ref> He played on defense and offense, occasionally as a forward passer.<ref name=\"Scarry in PD\" /> After a season in which the Rams contended for but lost the NFL's western division, Scarry spent the offseason as a student at [[Case Western Reserve University|Western Reserve University]] in Cleveland and served as the director of a [[YMCA]] camp in [[Mantua, Ohio]].<ref name=\"Scarry summer 1945\">{{cite news|title=Scarry and Reisz Will Be Back With Rams This Year|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=July 31, 1945|page=11}}</ref> Scarry suffered a knee injury near the beginning of the 1945 season, but soon returned to action as the Rams, led by quarterback [[Bob Waterfield]], won the [[1945 NFL Championship Game|NFL championship]].<ref name=\"Scarry injured\">{{cite news|title=Scarry and Lazetich Will Be Ready for Chicago Cardinals|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 25, 1945|page=11}}</ref><ref name=\"1945 Rams stats\">{{cite web|title=1945 Cleveland Rams Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/ram/1945.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |accessdate=August 11, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEAM0pXl?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/ram/1945.htm |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Scarry was the captain of the Rams during the championship run.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\" />\n\nThe Rams moved to [[Los Angeles]] after the 1945 season, and Scarry, along with teammates [[Chet Adams]], [[Tommy Colella]], [[Don Greenwood (American football)|Don Greenwood]] and [[Gaylon Smith]], decided to stay in Cleveland and play for the [[Cleveland Browns]], a team under formation in the new [[All-America Football Conference]].{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=26}} The Rams sought an injunction in Federal court to prevent Adams from defecting to the Browns, arguing that he was still under contract with the Rams despite the move. Adams argued that his contract described a team in Cleveland, and was no longer valid because of the Rams' relocation. A judge ruled in favor of Adams in August 1946, clearing the way for him and other former Rams players to join the Browns.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=26}}\n\nWhile Scarry was playing for the Browns, he was named head basketball coach at Western Reserve, where he had taken classes between games and in the offseason.<ref name=\"Scarry to play for Browns\">{{cite news|title=Center Scarry To Play For Browns|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=June 26, 1946|page=16}}</ref> In his first season, Scarry was a workhorse who often played between 50 and the full 60 minutes of games, lining up on the offensive and defensive lines.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\">{{cite news|last=Sauerbrei|first=Harold|title=Scarry Gets Defensive Signal Calling Test as Browns Tackle Dons Sunday|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=October 17, 1946|page=22}}</ref> Toward the middle of the season, Cleveland coach [[Paul Brown]] began to use him as the defensive leader, letting him call the unit's formations.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\" /> In December, Scarry's Western Reserve basketball team played its first games; he had missed numerous practices because of his duties with the Browns.<ref name=\"Reserve first game\">{{cite news|title=Reserve-B.-W. Cage Battle Tonight May Mark End of Keen Sports Rivalry|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 6, 1946|page=22}}</ref> The Browns went on to win the AAFC championship later in the month.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=64}}\n\nScarry remained with the Browns the following season. In September 1947 he received a bachelor of science degree from Western Reserve, completing an educational career at Waynesburg that was cut short by the war.<ref name=\"Scarry gets degree\">{{cite news|title=Forgets Moleskin to Get Sheepskin|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 18, 1947|page=21}}</ref> By October, he was mentioned as a possible successor to Tom Davies, who had resigned as Western Reserve's football coach. While still one of the AAFC's top centers, Scarry was bothered by injury and asthma and was considering leaving pro football.<ref name=\"Scarry considered at Reserve\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Charles|title=Scarry Reported as Prominent Candidate for Coaching Position at Reserve|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=October 29, 1947|page=25}}</ref> The Browns, meanwhile, won a second straight AAFC championship in December.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=81}} Scarry was named Western Reserve's football coach the following January, ending his career with the Browns.<ref name=\"Scarry signs as Reserve coach\">{{cite news|title=Scarry Signs 2-Year Contract at Reserve's Head Football Coach|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=January 29, 1948|page=17}}</ref> [[Frank Gatski]] took over as the Browns' regular center after Scarry's retirement.<ref name=\"Gatski takes over as Browns center\">{{cite news|last=Sauerbrei|first=Harold|title=Browns Get Tackle Palmer of Yankees; Waive Rights to Sarkisian|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 23, 1948|page=18}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\n\nScarry borrowed Paul Brown's coaching techniques at Western Reserve, instituting well-organized practices there. \"I had a lot of ideas about coaching before I went to work for the Browns,\" he said in 1947. \"But the manner in which Paul organized his practice and all his duties impressed me. I try to do the same here.\"<ref name=\"Scarry coaching technique\">{{cite news|last=Charles|first=Heaton|title=Seasons Change, But Old Man Moe Wins In Basketball As In Football|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 23, 1947|page=17}}</ref> With no good passer or runner and a lack of depth, Reserve's Red Cats performed poorly in Scarry's first season, but he was praised for making the most out of a thin squad.<ref name=\"Scarry first season at Reserve\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Charles|title=Improved Reserve Seeks 'Bonus' Victory Over Cincinnati|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=November 12, 1948|page=26|quote=Now the season is more than two thirds over for the University Circle school and, although its won and lost record is not good, Reserve has come along well under the ex-Browns center.}}</ref> In his second year in 1949, the Red Cats improved to a 4\u20135\u20131 record, and Scarry was expected to stay on for a third season.<ref name=\"Scarry record 1949\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Charles|title=Dedication of Field House Saturday Marks Watts' 18th Year at B.-W. Helm|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=November 29, 1949|page=24|quote=Scarry, who retired from professional football to take on the Reserve assignment, has completed his two-year contract but there is little doubt that the dark-haired Irishman will be retained.}}</ref> The following year, however, he resigned to take an assistant coaching position at [[Santa Clara University]] in [[California]] under former Browns assistant [[Richard F. Gallagher|Dick Gallagher]].<ref name=\"Scarry goes to Santa Clara\">{{cite news|title=Luther Gets Top Coaching Post|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wRAkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZX0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4846,160907&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 12, 2012|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|date=April 1, 1950|agency=Associated Press|location=Cleveland|page=15}}</ref>\n\nScarry stayed at Santa Clara for the 1950 and 1951 seasons before getting a job as an assistant at [[Loras College]] in [[Dubuque, Iowa]].<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\">{{cite web|title=Michael Scarry |url=http://www.wash-greenesportshall.org/2000/Scarry.htm |publisher=Pennsylvania Sports Hall of Fame |accessdate=August 12, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEAOiRls?url=http://www.wash-greenesportshall.org/2000/Scarry.htm |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He stayed at Loras for two years, moving to [[Washington State University]] in 1954.<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\" /> He left that school in November 1955 when head coach [[Al Kircher]] was fired in the wake of a 1\u201310 season.<ref name=\"Kircher fired\">{{cite news|title=Washington State Fires Coach Kircher|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=umhQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CxAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5139,3338675&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 12, 2012|newspaper=The Milwaukee Sentinel|date=November 22, 1955|agency=Associated Press|location=Pullman, Wash.|page=3}}</ref> In February 1956, he was hired as a line coach by the [[University of Cincinnati]].<ref name=\"Pinch Hitting\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|title=Pinch Hitting|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=February 18, 1956|page=23}}</ref><ref name=\"Scarry at Cincinnati\">{{cite news|title=Mike Scarry To Coach Line At Cincinnati|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=861&dat=19560211&id=E-E0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=_YcDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1219,3925695|accessdate=August 12, 2012|newspaper=Victoria Advocate|date=February 11, 1956|agency=United Press International|location=Cincinnati|page=5}}</ref> During his time at Cincinnati, Scarry served as an assistant to [[Otto Graham]], the former Browns star quarterback, as a coach in the [[College All-Star Game]], a now-defunct annual matchup between the NFL champion and a selection of the best college players from across the country.<ref name=\"Scarry in All-Star Game, 1961\">{{cite news|title=College All-Stars, 56 Strong, Report To Graham|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cQosAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wMYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1444,1291887&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=The Florence Times|date=July 13, 1961|agency=Associated Press|location=Evanston, Ill.|page=2}}</ref><ref name=\"Scarry in All-Star Game, 1962\">{{cite news|title=U-M's Miller Named To College All-Stars|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SiwyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pukFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1532,3418990&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=The Miami News|date=June 10, 1962|agency=Miami News Wire Service|location=Chicago|page=2C}}</ref>\n\nAfter seven seasons at Cincinnati, Scarry got his third head coaching job, for the [[Waynesburg Yellow Jackets football|Yellow Jackets]] at Waynesburg, his alma mater.<ref name=\"Scarry Waynesburg\">{{cite news|title=Scarry Given Miami-Buffalo Game Football|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2519&dat=19731208&id=auJdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AV8NAAAAIBAJ&pg=1598,1559977|accessdate=August 12, 2012|newspaper=Observer-Reporter|date=December 18, 1973|page=A8}}</ref> He was also the school's athletic director.<ref name=\"Scarry inducted into NAIA HOF\">{{cite news|title=Heinrick Resigns UPS Job|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BmQhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=54YFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4014,3529986&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=Tri City Herald|date=November 18, 1964|agency=Associated Press|location=Tacoma|page=26}}</ref> Scarry held the position for three seasons, from 1963 until 1965, and his teams had a 17\u20138\u20131 record during that span.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidearmdmg.com/waynesburg/football/ |title=Waynesberg College Football Media Guide |publisher=Sidearm DMG |accessdate=February 14, 2011 |page=79 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEAWMu4k?url=http://www.sidearmdmg.com/waynesburg/football/ |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Waynesburg won the Pennsylvania Intercollegiate Athletic Conference title in 1965, and Scarry was voted the conference's coach of the year.<ref name=\"Graham hires Scarry on Redskins\">{{cite news|title=Graham Hires Scarry to Coach Redskin Defense|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1298&dat=19660208&id=2f9NAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5YsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1339,4942928|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=The Free Lance-Star|date=February 8, 1966|location=Washington|page=9}}</ref> Scarry continued to act as the line coach under Graham for the college all-stars in the offseason during his tenure at Waynesburg.<ref name=\"Scarry on All-Stars, 1963\">{{cite news|title=Green Bay Favored Over College All-Stars|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TMgiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QJwFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4087,4111547&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=Reading Eagle|date=July 28, 1963|location=Chicago|page=34}}</ref><ref name=\"Scarry on All-Stars, 1965\">{{cite news|title=Names Graham to Coach 1965's All-Star Team|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fhxdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cloNAAAAIBAJ&pg=652,4238419&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=St. Joseph Gazette|date=June 10, 1965|agency=Associated Press|location=Chicago|page=3B}}</ref> In 1964, he was inducted into football hall of fame of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]], an association of smaller college sports programs.<ref name=\"Scarry inducted into NAIA HOF\" />\n\nGraham became the head coach of the NFL's [[Washington Redskins]] in 1966, and he hired Scarry that year as his defensive line coach.<ref name=\"Graham hires Scarry on Redskins\" /> Scarry stayed with the Redskins through 1968, when Graham resigned after three unsuccessful seasons. He then scouted briefly for the [[San Francisco 49ers]], [[Los Angeles Rams]] and [[Dallas Cowboys]] before taking a job in 1970 as the defensive line coach for the [[Miami Dolphins]] under [[Don Shula]], a former Browns player.<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\" /> Scarry spent the remainder of his coaching career with the Dolphins, retiring after 15 years in 1986.<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\" /> Miami reached the [[Super Bowl]] five times while Scarry was a coach there, winning the championship in [[Super Bowl VII|1972]] and [[Super Bowl VIII|1973]].<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\" />\n\n==Later life and death==\n\nAfter retiring from football, Scarry worked informally for the Dolphins as a volunteer assistant.<ref name=\"Scarry N-T obit\">{{cite news|title=Respected NFL, local coach Mo Scarry dies at age of 92 |url=http://www.news-press.com/article/20120911/SPORTS/309110017/Respected-NFL-local-coach-Mo-Scarry-dies-age-92?odyssey=nav%7Chead |accessdate=September 11, 2012 |newspaper=News-Times |date=September 10, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEAZWFrF?url=http://www.news-press.com/article/20120911/SPORTS/309110017/Respected-NFL-local-coach-Mo-Scarry-dies-age-92?odyssey=nav%7Chead |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He moved with his wife, Libby, to [[Fort Myers, Florida]] in 1994.<ref name=\"Scarry N-T obit\" /> Scarry was inducted into the Pennsylvania Sports Hall of Fame in 2000.<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\" /> He died in 2012 at his home in Fort Myers; he was the last surviving member of the original Browns team.<ref name=\"Scarry N-T obit\" /><ref name=\"Scarry Browns obit\">{{cite news|last=Florjancic |first=Matt |title=Michael Scarry passes away |url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-1/Michael-Scarry-passes-away/cd280e33-27cc-418d-bb50-640fcd5ce744 |accessdate=September 11, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Browns |date=September 11, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEAcBVBt?url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-1/Michael-Scarry-passes-away/cd280e33-27cc-418d-bb50-640fcd5ce744 |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He had four sons and a daughter.<ref name=\"Scarry Browns obit\" /> Mike was also the brother of professional basketball player [[Jack Scarry]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://peachbasketsociety.blogspot.com/2016/01/jack-scarry.html| title=Jack Scarry | publisher=Blogspot | work=Peach Basket Society | accessdate=March 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Piascik|first=Andy|year=2007|title=The Best Show in Football: The 1946\u20131955 Cleveland Browns|publisher=Taylor Trade Publishing|location=Lanham, MD|isbn=978-1-58979-571-6|ref={{sfnRef|Piascik|2007}} }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=2524996 |espn= |cbs= |yahoo= |si= |pfr=S/ScarMi20 |rotoworld= }}\n* {{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{Navboxes| list1 =\n{{Case Western Spartans football coach navbox}}\n{{Loras Duhawks football coach navbox}}\n{{Waynesburg Yellow Jackets football coach navbox}}\n{{1945 Cleveland Rams}}\n{{1946 Cleveland Browns}}\n{{1947 Cleveland Browns}}\n{{Super Bowl VII}}\n{{Super Bowl VIII}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scarry, Mo}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football centers]]\n[[Category:Case Western Spartans football coaches]]\n[[Category:Case Western Spartans men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bearcats football coaches]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns (AAFC) players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Rams players]]\n[[Category:Loras Duhawks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Miami Dolphins coaches]]\n[[Category:Santa Clara Broncos football coaches]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins coaches]]\n[[Category:Washington State Cougars football coaches]]\n[[Category:Waynesburg Yellow Jackets athletic directors]]\n[[Category:Waynesburg Yellow Jackets football coaches]]\n[[Category:Waynesburg Yellow Jackets football players]]\n[[Category:Waynesburg Yellow Jackets men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Waynesburg Yellow Jackets men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:People from Duquesne, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=Michael Scarry\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|alt=\n|caption=\n|number=20\n|position=[[Center (American football)|Center]], [[Tackle (American football)|Tackle]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1920|2|1}}\n|birth_place=[[Duquesne, Pennsylvania]]\n|death_date= {{death date and age|2012|9|9|1920|2|1}}\n|death_place=[[Fort Myers, Florida]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=0\n|weight_lbs=214\n|high_school=[[Duquesne High School|Duquesne (PA)]]\n|college=[[Waynesburg Yellow Jackets football|Waynesburg College]]\n|pastteams=\n* [[Cleveland Rams]] ({{NFL Year|1944}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1945}})\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ([[All-America Football Conference#1946|1946]]\u2013[[All-America Football Conference#1947|1947]])\n|pastcoaching=\n* [[Case Western Reserve Spartans football|Western Reserve]] ([[Head coach|HC]]) [[1948 college football season|1948]]\u2013[[1949 college football season|1949]]\n* [[Santa Clara Broncos football|Santa Clara University]] (Asst.) [[1950 college football season|1950]]\u2013[[1951 college football season|1951]]\n* [[Loras Duhawks football|Loras College]] ([[Head coach|HC]]) [[1952 college football season|1952]]\u2013[[1953 college football season|1953]]\n* [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington State University]] (Asst.) [[1954 college football season|1954]]\u2013[[1955 college football season|1955]]\n* [[University of Cincinnati]] ([[American football positions#Defensive line|DL]]) [[1956 college football season|1956]]\u2013[[1962 college football season|1962]]\n* [[Waynesburg Yellow Jackets|Waynesburg College]] ([[Head coach|HC]]) [[1963 college football season|1963]]\u2013[[1965 college football season|1965]]\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ([[American football positions#Defensive line|DL]]) {{NFL Year|1966}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1968}}\n* Scout, various teams {{NFL Year|1969}}\n* [[Miami Dolphins]] ([[American football positions#Defensive line|DL]]) {{NFL Year|1970}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1985}}\n|highlights=\n* [[NFL Championship|NFL Champion]] ([[1945 NFL Championship Game|1945]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[All-America Football Conference|AAFC Champion]] ([[All-America Football Conference#1946|1946]], [[All-America Football Conference#1947|1947]])\n* Member, Pennsylvania Sports Hall of Fame\n|statseason=1947\n|statlabel1=Games\n|statvalue1=45\n|statlabel2=Interceptions\n|statvalue2=7\n|nflnew=mikescarry/2524996\n|pfr=ScarMi20\n}}\n\n'''Michael Joseph \"Mo\" Scarry''' (February 1, 1920 \u2013 September 9, 2012) was an [[American football]] player and coach. He grew up in [[Pennsylvania]] and was a star on his high school basketball team. Scarry played football in college at [[Waynesburg University|Waynesburg College]] in [[Waynesburg, Pennsylvania]] and went on to join the [[Cleveland Rams]] in the [[National Football League]] as a [[center (American football)|center]] following a stint in the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] during [[World War II]]. The Rams moved to Los Angeles after winning the [[1945 NFL Championship Game|1945 NFL championship]], and Scarry elected to stay in Cleveland and play for the [[Cleveland Browns]] under coach [[Paul Brown]] in the new [[All-America Football Conference]]. The Browns won the AAFC championship in 1946 and 1947 while Scarry was on the team.\n\nScarry, who coached the basketball team at [[Case Western Reserve University|Western Reserve University]] in Cleveland during his playing career, retired from pro football after the 1947 season to take up a post as head coach of the school's football team. He stayed there for two seasons before moving to [[Santa Clara University]] in [[California]] as an assistant coach. Scarry then moved in 1952 to [[Loras College]] in [[Iowa]] as an assistant. After a stint at [[Washington State University]], he spent six years as the line coach for the [[University of Cincinnati]]. Scarry served as head football coach at Waynesburg, his alma mater, for three seasons between 1963 and 1965. He got his first professional coaching job in 1966 with the NFL's [[Washington Redskins]], the following year, and became the defensive line coach of the [[Miami Dolphins]] three years later. He stayed with the Dolphins for 15 seasons until his retirement; during his Dolphins career, the team won two [[Super Bowl]]s. Scarry was inducted into the Pennsylvania Sports Hall of Fame in 2000.\n\n==High school, college and military service==\n\nScarry grew up in [[Duquesne, Pennsylvania]], where he was a star on his high school basketball team.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\" /> He also played football, but was not a standout.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\" /> Scarry attended [[Waynesburg University|Waynesburg College]], a small school in [[Waynesburg, Pennsylvania]], where he continued to play football and basketball.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\" /><ref name=\"Scarry joins Rams\">{{cite news|title=Rams Need Strengthening at End and Tackle Posts|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=August 27, 1944|page=2C}}</ref><ref name=\"Scarry in PD\">{{cite news|title=Raging Ram Rookie|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=November 12, 1944|page=2C|quote=Mike Scarry, 210-pound center of the Cleveland Rams who played his collegiate football at Waynesburg and hails from Duquesne, Pa. ... Mike rates as one of the rookie finds of the year.}}</ref> He served in the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] during [[World War II]] in [[North Africa]], but came down with asthma and was given a medical discharge.<ref name=\"Scarry considered at Reserve\" /> He signed with the [[Cleveland Rams]] of the [[National Football League]] starting in 1944.<ref name=\"Scarry joins Rams\" />\n\n==Professional career==\n\nScarry began the 1944 season with the Rams at left tackle, but was shifted to center in September.<ref name=\"Scarry shifted to center\">{{cite news|last=Dietrich|first=John|title=Conkright Will Be Regular End For Ram Eleven|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 12, 1944|page=13|quote=Mike Scarry, the Rams' rookie tackle from Waynesburg, also has been changed to center.}}</ref> He played on defense and offense, occasionally as a forward passer.<ref name=\"Scarry in PD\" /> After a season in which the Rams contended for but lost the NFL's western division, Scarry spent the offseason as a student at [[Case Western Reserve University|Western Reserve University]] in Cleveland and served as the director of a [[YMCA]] camp in [[Mantua, Ohio]].<ref name=\"Scarry summer 1945\">{{cite news|title=Scarry and Reisz Will Be Back With Rams This Year|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=July 31, 1945|page=11}}</ref> Scarry suffered a knee injury near the beginning of the 1945 season, but soon returned to action as the Rams, led by quarterback [[Bob Waterfield]], won the [[1945 NFL Championship Game|NFL championship]].<ref name=\"Scarry injured\">{{cite news|title=Scarry and Lazetich Will Be Ready for Chicago Cardinals|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 25, 1945|page=11}}</ref><ref name=\"1945 Rams stats\">{{cite web|title=1945 Cleveland Rams Statistics & Players |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/ram/1945.htm |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |accessdate=August 11, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEAM0pXl?url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/ram/1945.htm |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Scarry was the captain of the Rams during the championship run.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\" />\n\nThe Rams moved to [[Los Angeles]] after the 1945 season, and Scarry, along with teammates [[Chet Adams]], [[Tommy Colella]], [[Don Greenwood (American football)|Don Greenwood]] and [[Gaylon Smith]], decided to stay in Cleveland and play for the [[Cleveland Browns]], a team under formation in the new [[All-America Football Conference]].{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=26}} The Rams sought an injunction in Federal court to prevent Adams from defecting to the Browns, arguing that he was still under contract with the Rams despite the move. Adams argued that his contract described a team in Cleveland, and was no longer valid because of the Rams' relocation. A judge ruled in favor of Adams in August 1946, clearing the way for him and other former Rams players to join the Browns.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=26}}\n\nWhile Scarry was playing for the Browns, he was named head basketball coach at Western Reserve, where he had taken classes between games and in the offseason.<ref name=\"Scarry to play for Browns\">{{cite news|title=Center Scarry To Play For Browns|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=June 26, 1946|page=16}}</ref> In his first season, Scarry was a workhorse who often played between 50 and the full 60 minutes of games, lining up on the offensive and defensive lines.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\">{{cite news|last=Sauerbrei|first=Harold|title=Scarry Gets Defensive Signal Calling Test as Browns Tackle Dons Sunday|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=October 17, 1946|page=22}}</ref> Toward the middle of the season, Cleveland coach [[Paul Brown]] began to use him as the defensive leader, letting him call the unit's formations.<ref name=\"Scarry as ironman\" /> In December, Scarry's Western Reserve basketball team played its first games; he had missed numerous practices because of his duties with the Browns.<ref name=\"Reserve first game\">{{cite news|title=Reserve-B.-W. Cage Battle Tonight May Mark End of Keen Sports Rivalry|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 6, 1946|page=22}}</ref> The Browns went on to win the AAFC championship later in the month.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=64}}\n\nScarry remained with the Browns the following season. In September 1947 he received a bachelor of science degree from Western Reserve, completing an educational career at Waynesburg that was cut short by the war.<ref name=\"Scarry gets degree\">{{cite news|title=Forgets Moleskin to Get Sheepskin|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=September 18, 1947|page=21}}</ref> By October, he was mentioned as a possible successor to Tom Davies, who had resigned as Western Reserve's football coach. While still one of the AAFC's top centers, Scarry was bothered by injury and asthma and was considering leaving pro football.<ref name=\"Scarry considered at Reserve\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Charles|title=Scarry Reported as Prominent Candidate for Coaching Position at Reserve|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=October 29, 1947|page=25}}</ref> The Browns, meanwhile, won a second straight AAFC championship in December.{{sfn|Piascik|2007|p=81}} Scarry was named Western Reserve's football coach the following January, ending his career with the Browns.<ref name=\"Scarry signs as Reserve coach\">{{cite news|title=Scarry Signs 2-Year Contract at Reserve's Head Football Coach|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=January 29, 1948|page=17}}</ref> [[Frank Gatski]] took over as the Browns' regular center after Scarry's retirement.<ref name=\"Gatski takes over as Browns center\">{{cite news|last=Sauerbrei|first=Harold|title=Browns Get Tackle Palmer of Yankees; Waive Rights to Sarkisian|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 23, 1948|page=18}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\n\nScarry borrowed Paul Brown's coaching techniques at Western Reserve, instituting well-organized practices there. \"I had a lot of ideas about coaching before I went to work for the Browns,\" he said in 1947. \"But the manner in which Paul organized his practice and all his duties impressed me. I try to do the same here.\"<ref name=\"Scarry coaching technique\">{{cite news|last=Charles|first=Heaton|title=Seasons Change, But Old Man Moe Wins In Basketball As In Football|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=December 23, 1947|page=17}}</ref> With no good passer or runner and a lack of depth, Reserve's Red Cats performed poorly in Scarry's first season, but he was praised for making the most out of a thin squad.<ref name=\"Scarry first season at Reserve\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Charles|title=Improved Reserve Seeks 'Bonus' Victory Over Cincinnati|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=November 12, 1948|page=26|quote=Now the season is more than two thirds over for the University Circle school and, although its won and lost record is not good, Reserve has come along well under the ex-Browns center.}}</ref> In his second year in 1949, the Red Cats improved to a 4\u20135\u20131 record, and Scarry was expected to stay on for a third season.<ref name=\"Scarry record 1949\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Charles|title=Dedication of Field House Saturday Marks Watts' 18th Year at B.-W. Helm|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=November 29, 1949|page=24|quote=Scarry, who retired from professional football to take on the Reserve assignment, has completed his two-year contract but there is little doubt that the dark-haired Irishman will be retained.}}</ref> The following year, however, he resigned to take an assistant coaching position at [[Santa Clara University]] in [[California]] under former Browns assistant [[Richard F. Gallagher|Dick Gallagher]].<ref name=\"Scarry goes to Santa Clara\">{{cite news|title=Luther Gets Top Coaching Post|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wRAkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZX0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4846,160907&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 12, 2012|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|date=April 1, 1950|agency=Associated Press|location=Cleveland|page=15}}</ref>\n\nScarry stayed at Santa Clara for the 1950 and 1951 seasons before getting a job as an assistant at [[Loras College]] in [[Dubuque, Iowa]].<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\">{{cite web|title=Michael Scarry |url=http://www.wash-greenesportshall.org/2000/Scarry.htm |publisher=Pennsylvania Sports Hall of Fame |accessdate=August 12, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEAOiRls?url=http://www.wash-greenesportshall.org/2000/Scarry.htm |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He stayed at Loras for two years, moving to [[Washington State University]] in 1954.<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\" /> He left that school in November 1955 when head coach [[Al Kircher]] was fired in the wake of a 1\u201310 season.<ref name=\"Kircher fired\">{{cite news|title=Washington State Fires Coach Kircher|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=umhQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CxAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5139,3338675&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 12, 2012|newspaper=The Milwaukee Sentinel|date=November 22, 1955|agency=Associated Press|location=Pullman, Wash.|page=3}}</ref> In February 1956, he was hired as a line coach by the [[University of Cincinnati]].<ref name=\"Pinch Hitting\">{{cite news|last=Heaton|first=Chuck|title=Pinch Hitting|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=February 18, 1956|page=23}}</ref><ref name=\"Scarry at Cincinnati\">{{cite news|title=Mike Scarry To Coach Line At Cincinnati|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=861&dat=19560211&id=E-E0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=_YcDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1219,3925695|accessdate=August 12, 2012|newspaper=Victoria Advocate|date=February 11, 1956|agency=United Press International|location=Cincinnati|page=5}}</ref> During his time at Cincinnati, Scarry served as an assistant to [[Otto Graham]], the former Browns star quarterback, as a coach in the [[College All-Star Game]], a now-defunct annual matchup between the NFL champion and a selection of the best college players from across the country.<ref name=\"Scarry in All-Star Game, 1961\">{{cite news|title=College All-Stars, 56 Strong, Report To Graham|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cQosAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wMYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1444,1291887&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=The Florence Times|date=July 13, 1961|agency=Associated Press|location=Evanston, Ill.|page=2}}</ref><ref name=\"Scarry in All-Star Game, 1962\">{{cite news|title=U-M's Miller Named To College All-Stars|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SiwyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pukFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1532,3418990&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=The Miami News|date=June 10, 1962|agency=Miami News Wire Service|location=Chicago|page=2C}}</ref>\n\nAfter seven seasons at Cincinnati, Scarry got his third head coaching job, for the [[Waynesburg Yellow Jackets football|Yellow Jackets]] at Waynesburg, his alma mater.<ref name=\"Scarry Waynesburg\">{{cite news|title=Scarry Given Miami-Buffalo Game Football|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2519&dat=19731208&id=auJdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AV8NAAAAIBAJ&pg=1598,1559977|accessdate=August 12, 2012|newspaper=Observer-Reporter|date=December 18, 1973|page=A8}}</ref> He was also the school's athletic director.<ref name=\"Scarry inducted into NAIA HOF\">{{cite news|title=Heinrick Resigns UPS Job|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BmQhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=54YFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4014,3529986&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=Tri City Herald|date=November 18, 1964|agency=Associated Press|location=Tacoma|page=26}}</ref> Scarry held the position for three seasons, from 1963 until 1965, and his teams had a 17\u20138\u20131 record during that span.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidearmdmg.com/waynesburg/football/ |title=Waynesberg College Football Media Guide |publisher=Sidearm DMG |accessdate=February 14, 2011 |page=79 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEAWMu4k?url=http://www.sidearmdmg.com/waynesburg/football/ |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Waynesburg won the Pennsylvania Intercollegiate Athletic Conference title in 1965, and Scarry was voted the conference's coach of the year.<ref name=\"Graham hires Scarry on Redskins\">{{cite news|title=Graham Hires Scarry to Coach Redskin Defense|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1298&dat=19660208&id=2f9NAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5YsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1339,4942928|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=The Free Lance-Star|date=February 8, 1966|location=Washington|page=9}}</ref> Scarry continued to act as the line coach under Graham for the college all-stars in the offseason during his tenure at Waynesburg.<ref name=\"Scarry on All-Stars, 1963\">{{cite news|title=Green Bay Favored Over College All-Stars|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TMgiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QJwFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4087,4111547&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=Reading Eagle|date=July 28, 1963|location=Chicago|page=34}}</ref><ref name=\"Scarry on All-Stars, 1965\">{{cite news|title=Names Graham to Coach 1965's All-Star Team|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fhxdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cloNAAAAIBAJ&pg=652,4238419&dq=mike-scarry&hl=en|accessdate=August 13, 2012|newspaper=St. Joseph Gazette|date=June 10, 1965|agency=Associated Press|location=Chicago|page=3B}}</ref> In 1964, he was inducted into football hall of fame of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]], an association of smaller college sports programs.<ref name=\"Scarry inducted into NAIA HOF\" />\n\nGraham became the head coach of the NFL's [[Washington Redskins]] in 1966, and he hired Scarry that year as his defensive line coach.<ref name=\"Graham hires Scarry on Redskins\" /> Scarry stayed with the Redskins through 1968, when Graham resigned after three unsuccessful seasons. He then scouted briefly for the [[San Francisco 49ers]], [[Los Angeles Rams]] and [[Dallas Cowboys]] before taking a job in 1970 as the defensive line coach for the [[Miami Dolphins]] under [[Don Shula]], a former Browns player.<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\" /> Scarry spent the remainder of his coaching career with the Dolphins, retiring after 15 years in 1986.<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\" /> Miami reached the [[Super Bowl]] five times while Scarry was a coach there, winning the championship in [[Super Bowl VII|1972]] and [[Super Bowl VIII|1973]].<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\" />\n\n==Later life and death==\n\nAfter retiring from football, Scarry worked informally for the Dolphins as a volunteer assistant.<ref name=\"Scarry N-T obit\">{{cite news|title=Respected NFL, local coach Mo Scarry dies at age of 92 |url=http://www.news-press.com/article/20120911/SPORTS/309110017/Respected-NFL-local-coach-Mo-Scarry-dies-age-92?odyssey=nav%7Chead |accessdate=September 11, 2012 |newspaper=News-Times |date=September 10, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEAZWFrF?url=http://www.news-press.com/article/20120911/SPORTS/309110017/Respected-NFL-local-coach-Mo-Scarry-dies-age-92?odyssey=nav%7Chead |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He moved with his wife, Libby, to [[Fort Myers, Florida]] in 1994.<ref name=\"Scarry N-T obit\" /> Scarry was inducted into the Pennsylvania Sports Hall of Fame in 2000.<ref name=\"Scarry Pennsylvania HOF page\" /> He died in 2012 at his home in Fort Myers; he was the last surviving member of the original Browns team.<ref name=\"Scarry N-T obit\" /><ref name=\"Scarry Browns obit\">{{cite news|last=Florjancic |first=Matt |title=Michael Scarry passes away |url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-1/Michael-Scarry-passes-away/cd280e33-27cc-418d-bb50-640fcd5ce744 |accessdate=September 11, 2012 |newspaper=Cleveland Browns |date=September 11, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEAcBVBt?url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/article-1/Michael-Scarry-passes-away/cd280e33-27cc-418d-bb50-640fcd5ce744 |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He had four sons and a daughter.<ref name=\"Scarry Browns obit\" /> Mike was also the brother of professional basketball player [[Jack Scarry]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://peachbasketsociety.blogspot.com/2016/01/jack-scarry.html| title=Jack Scarry | publisher=Blogspot | work=Peach Basket Society | accessdate=March 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Piascik|first=Andy|year=2007|title=The Best Show in Football: The 1946\u20131955 Cleveland Browns|publisher=Taylor Trade Publishing|location=Lanham, MD|isbn=978-1-58979-571-6|ref={{sfnRef|Piascik|2007}} }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=2524996 |espn= |cbs= |yahoo= |si= |pfr=S/ScarMi20 |rotoworld= }}\n* {{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{Navboxes| list1 =\n{{Case Western Spartans football coach navbox}}\n{{Loras Duhawks football coach navbox}}\n{{Waynesburg Yellow Jackets football coach navbox}}\n{{1945 Cleveland Rams}}\n{{1946 Cleveland Browns}}\n{{1947 Cleveland Browns}}\n{{Super Bowl VII}}\n{{Super Bowl VIII}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scarry, Mo}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football centers]]\n[[Category:Case Western Spartans football coaches]]\n[[Category:Case Western Spartans men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bearcats football coaches]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns (AAFC) players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Rams players]]\n[[Category:Loras Duhawks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Miami Dolphins coaches]]\n[[Category:Santa Clara Broncos football coaches]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins coaches]]\n[[Category:Washington State Cougars football coaches]]\n[[Category:Waynesburg Yellow Jackets athletic directors]]\n[[Category:Waynesburg Yellow Jackets football coaches]]\n[[Category:Waynesburg Yellow Jackets football players]]\n[[Category:Waynesburg Yellow Jackets men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Waynesburg Yellow Jackets men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:People from Duquesne, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n", "name_user": "Wizardman", "label": "safe", "comment": "can't find anything on that", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Scarry"}
{"title_page": "Richard Atherton", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{No footnotes|date=January 2020}}\n{{Cleanup|reason=References need to be properly formatted and inline citations used. Pleaase see [[WP:REFB]]|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use British English|date = January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = January 2020}}\n\nSir '''Richard Atherton''', [[Tory]] politician and an English [[Member of Parliament]] elected in 1671 representing [[Liverpool (UK Parliament constituency)]]. He also served at Lord Mayor from 1684 to 1685. He resided at [[Bewsey Old Hall]],  [[Warrington]] and died in 1687.\n\n==Early Life==\n\nBorn in Warrington on 22nd September 1656, the son of John Atherton and Mary Rawsthone. His father served as a Captain in the [[parliamentary army]] during the [[English Civil War]]. Later he served twice as Sheriff of Lancaster under the [[Lord Protector]] [[Oliver Cromwell]].\n\nHe was educated at [[Brasenose College, Oxford]] in 1672 and [[Grays Inn]] in 1675.\n\nHe inherited [[Bewsey Old Hall]] from Dame Margaret Ireland upon her death in 1675.  \n\nHe married Isabel, the daughter of Richard Holt on 22 November 1676. They had one son Jonathan. He married Agnes, the daughter of Miles Dodding of Conishead on 1 November 1686.\n\n==Political Career==\n\nWhilst his father had been a parliamentarian who fought against the royalists, his political career took place during the period of Restoration covering the reign of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] (1660\u20131685) and the brief reign of his younger brother [[James II]] (1685\u20131688).\n\nHe was Knighted months after the aftermath of the [[Rye House Plot]] of 1683 (a plot to assassinate the King), a period of trials and executions. These were politically turbulent times, leading to the rebellion of 1685, the [[Monmouth Rebellion]] and [[Argyll's Rising]].\n\nHis terms in office from Member of Parliament, to Mayor and to Alderman of Liverpool, covered the whole Restoration period of Stuart monarchs, a period which ended with the death of [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]].\n\n==Member of Parliament==\nHe was elected as Member of Parliament for Liverpool in 1671, but was unseated on petition.\n\n==Lord Mayor of Liverpool==\nIn 1684 he became [[Lord Mayor of Liverpool]]. He secured the surrender of the Liverpool Charter, which was delivered to [[George Jeffreys, 1st Baron Jeffreys]], known as Judge Jeffreys at Bewsey Old Hall in 1684. The notes on the Liverpool Charters refer you him as the first modern Mayor of Liverpool. \n\nHe was knighted on 22 June 1684 by [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]] at [[Windsor Castle]].\n\n==Death==\n\nHe died in Warrington and was buried there on 11 January 1687.\n\n==References==\n\n* {{cite web |title=The House of Commons, 1660-1690{{!}} | url=\nhttp://books.google.com/books?id=HW1_upECKUwC&pg=PA288&lpg=PA288&dq=richard+atherton.lord.mayor+liverpool&source=bl&ots=MuEfJaypb9&sig=ACfU3U0fe3vF6HWMuK310-8cVTvydGY5LA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjaoeCwrMjmAhXMMd8KHTXDBPoQ6AEwC3oECAUQAQ#v=onepage&q=Atherton&f=false\n|accessdate=21 December 2019}}\n\n* {{cite web |title= Liverpool Town Hall - MAYORS OF THE CITY OF LIVERPOOL SINCE 1207{{!}} | url=\nhttp://www.liverpooltownhall.co.uk/former-mayors-lord-mayors-city-liverpool/|accessdate=21 December 2019}}\n\n* {{cite web |title=Transactions of the Historic Society of Lancashire and Cheshire, Volumes 35-37 - Liverpool Charters{{!}} | url=\nhttp://books.google.com/books?id=870xAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA70&lpg=RA1-PA70&dq=atherton+jeffies+bewsey&source=bl&ots=JTCemMjoDa&sig=ACfU3U3CJfHekVVDieu8dWAoFdPZUzEewA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwitk-er4MnmAhVlRN8KHZ2VB5cQ6AEwAHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=atherton%20jeffies%20bewsey&f=false/ |accessdate=22 December 2019}}\n\n* {{cite web |title=The Rise and Progress of Liverpool from 1551 to 1835 {{!}} | url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bBc5AQAAMAAJ&q=sir+richard+atherton+mp+liverpool&dq=sir+richard+atherton+mp+liverpool&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjBkeWrysfmAhXmQhUIHeqhCIY4ChDoATACegQIARAR |accessdate=21 December 2019}}\n\n* {{cite web |title=Local Gleanings Relating to Lancashire and Cheshire: V.1-2, April 1875-Dec. 1878 {{!}} | url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DtJCAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA215&dq=sir+richard+atherton+mp&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiuism9x8fmAhUMCsAKHUmXCwsQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=sir%20richard%20atherton%20mp&f=false |accessdate=21 December 2019}}\n\n* {{cite web |title=Liverpool 1660-1750: People, Prosperity and Power |url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=A2xnAAAAMAAJ&q=sir+richard+atherton+mp+liverpool&dq=sir+richard+atherton+mp+liverpool&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjhjqzZyMfmAhWoQkEAHZs4CGAQ6AEIQjAE |accessdate=21 December 2019}}\n\n* {{cite web |title=History of the Commerce and Town of Liverpool: And of the Rise of ..., Volume 1 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=uBYVAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA354&lpg=PA354&dq=richard+atherton.lord.mayor+liverpool&source=bl&ots=Mun2NM-EjR&sig=ACfU3U318sH8l89zEJvD-WGVhNxKU66vmw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjaoeCwrMjmAhXMMd8KHTXDBPoQ6AEwDHoECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=atherton&f=false\n|accessdate=21 December 2019}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:1656 births]]\n[[Category:17th-century English politicians]]\n[[Category:1687 deaths]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Liverpool]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{No footnotes|date=January 2020}}\n{{Cleanup|reason=References need to be properly formatted and inline citations used. Pleaase see [[WP:REFB]]|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use British English|date = January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = January 2020}}\n\nSir '''Richard Atherton''', [[Tory]] politician and an English [[Member of Parliament]] elected in 1671 representing [[Liverpool (UK Parliament constituency)]]. He also served at Lord Mayor from 1684 to 1685. He resided at [[Bewsey Old Hall]],  [[Warrington]] and died in 1687.\n\n==Early Life==\n\nBorn in Warrington on 22nd September 1656, the son of John Atherton and Mary Rawsthone. His father served as a Captain in the [[parliamentary army]] during the [[English Civil War]]. Later he served twice as Sheriff of Lancaster under the [[Lord Protector]] [[Oliver Cromwell]].\n\nHe was educated at [[Brasenose College, Oxford]] in 1672 and [[Grays Inn]] in 1675.\n\nHe inherited [[Bewsey Old Hall]] from Dame Margaret Ireland upon her death in 1675.  \n\nHe married Isabel, the daughter of Richard Holt on 22 November 1676. They had one son Jonathan. He married Agnes, the daughter of Miles Dodding of Conishead on 1 November 1686.\n\n==Political Career==\n\nWhilst his father had been a parliamentarian who fought against the royalists, his political career took place during the period of Restoration covering the reign of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] (1660\u20131685) and the brief reign of his younger brother [[James II]] (1685\u20131688).\n\nHe was Knighted months after the aftermath of the [[Rye House Plot]] of 1683 (a plot to assassinate the King), a period of trials and executions. These were politically turbulent times, leading to the rebellion of 1685, the [[Monmouth Rebellion]] and [[Argyll's Rising]].\n\nHis terms in office from Member of Parliament, to Mayor and to Alderman of Liverpool, covered the whole Restoration period of Stuart monarchs, a period which ended with the death of [[Queen Anne]].\n\n==Member of Parliament==\nHe was elected as Member of Parliament for Liverpool in 1671, but was unseated on petition.\n\n==Lord Mayor of Liverpool==\nIn 1684 he became [[Lord Mayor of Liverpool]]. He secured the surrender of the Liverpool Charter, which was delivered to [[George Jeffreys, 1st Baron Jeffreys]], known as Judge Jeffreys at Bewsey Old Hall in 1684. The notes on the Liverpool Charters refer you him as the first modern Mayor of Liverpool. \n\nHe was knighted on 22 June 1684 by [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]] at [[Windsor Castle]].\n\n==Death==\n\nHe died in Warrington and was buried there on 11 January 1687.\n\n==References==\n\n* {{cite web |title=The House of Commons, 1660-1690{{!}} | url=\nhttp://books.google.com/books